{"title_page": "Jeffrey Koplan", "text_new": "{{short description|American epidemiologist and physician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Jeffrey P. Koplan\n| image               = Jeffrey_P._Koplan.jpg\n| office              = Director of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]\n| president           = \n| term_start          = October 5, 1998\n| term_end            = March 31, 2002\n| predecessor         = [[David Satcher]]\n| successor           = [[Julie Gerberding]]\n| president           = [[Bill Clinton]]<br/>[[George W. Bush]]\n| birth_name          = \n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = [[Boston]], Massachusetts<ref name=\"Epi\"/> \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Yale University]]<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Public Health|MPH]])<br/>[[Mt. Sinai School of Medicine]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])\n}}\n\n'''Jeffrey P. Koplan''' is the Vice President for Global Health at [[Emory University]] after having established and serving as the Director of the Emory Global Health Institute from 2006-2013.<ref name=\"Grandrounds\">{{cite web |title=Seven Decades of Firsts with Seven CDC Directors |url=https://www.cdc.gov/grand-rounds/pp/2016/20160712-pdf-seven-directors-koplan-508.pdf |website=CDC |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>  Koplan was the director of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] from 1998<ref>{{Cite press release |title=SHALALA APPOINTS JEFFREY P. KOPLAN TO HEAD CDC |date=July 10, 1998 |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/pressrel/r980710.htm |language=English |access-date=April 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421004302/https://www.cdc.gov/media/pressrel/r980710.htm |archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> to 2002;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/about/history/pastdirectors.htm|title=Past CDC Directors/Administrators {{!}} About {{!}} CDC|date=2018-07-20|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> he had previously worked at the CDC for more than twenty years, looking into [[Contaminated haemophilia blood products|HIV-contaminated blood]], as well as the [[Bhopal disaster]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stolberg |first=Sheryl Gay |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/10/us/epidemiologist-is-chosen-to-head-centers-for-disease-control.html |title=Epidemiologist Is Chosen to Head Centers for Disease Control |date=July 10, 1998 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During his tenure as Director, he fought syphilis,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stolberg |first=Sheryl Gay |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/10/08/us/us-says-stars-are-aligned-to-vanquish-an-old-foe-syphilis.html |title=U.S. Says 'Stars Are Aligned' to Vanquish an Old Foe: Syphilis |date=October 8, 1999 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and supervised the investigation into the [[2001 anthrax attacks]];<ref>{{Cite news |last=Altman |first=Lawrence K. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/13/science/the-doctor-s-world-when-everything-changed-at-the-cdc.html |title=THE DOCTOR'S WORLD; When Everything Changed at the C.D.C. |date=November 13, 2001 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=|language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> before leaving the agency in March 2002.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pear |first=Robert |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/22/us/embattled-disease-agency-chief-is-quitting.html |title=Embattled Disease Agency Chief Is Quitting |date=February 22, 2002 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nKoplan earned a bachelor's degree in English from [[Yale University]], a master's degree in public health from [[Harvard University]] and a medical doctorate from the [[Mt. Sinai School of Medicine]].<ref name=\"Epi\">{{cite news |last1=McClam |first1=Erin |title=CDC Chief Jeffrey Koplan Resigns |url=https://www.ph.ucla.edu/epi/bioter/koplanresigns.html |accessdate=16 April 2020 |publisher=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[David Satcher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = Director of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|years=1998-2002}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Julie Gerberding]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koplan, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:Directors of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]\n[[Category:Yale College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard School of Public Health alumni]]\n[[Category:Mount Sinai School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Emory University faculty]]\n[[Category:Centers for Disease Control and Prevention people]]\n[[Category:People from Boston]]\n\n\n{{US-med-bio-stub}}\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American epidemiologist and physician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Jeffrey P. Koplan\n| image               = Jeffrey_P._Koplan.jpg\n| office              = Director of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]\n| president           = \n| term_start          = October 5, 1998\n| term_end            = March 31, 2002\n| predecessor         = [[David Satcher]]\n| successor           = [[Julie Gerberding]]\n| president           = [[Bill Clinton]]<br/>[[George W. Bush]]\n| birth_name          = \n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = [[Boston]], Massachusetts<ref name=\"Epi\"/> \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Yale University]]<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Public Health|MPH]])<br/>[[Mt. Sinai School of Medicine]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])\n}}\n\n'''Jeffrey P. Koplan''' is the Vice President for Global Health at [[Emory University]] after having established and serving as the Director of the Emory Global Health Institute from 2006-2013.<ref name=\"Grandrounds\">{{cite web |title=Seven Decades of Firsts with Seven CDC Directors |url=https://www.cdc.gov/grand-rounds/pp/2016/20160712-pdf-seven-directors-koplan-508.pdf |website=CDC |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>  Koplan was the director of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] from 1998<ref>{{Cite press release |title=SHALALA APPOINTS JEFFREY P. KOPLAN TO HEAD CDC |date=July 10, 1998 |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/pressrel/r980710.htm |language=English |access-date=April 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421004302/https://www.cdc.gov/media/pressrel/r980710.htm |archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> to 2002;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/about/history/pastdirectors.htm|title=Past CDC Directors/Administrators {{!}} About {{!}} CDC|date=2018-07-20|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> he had previously worked at the CDC for more than twenty years, looking into [[Contaminated haemophilia blood products|HIV-contaminated blood]], as well as the [[Bhopal disaster]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stolberg |first=Sheryl Gay |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/10/us/epidemiologist-is-chosen-to-head-centers-for-disease-control.html |title=Epidemiologist Is Chosen to Head Centers for Disease Control |date=July 10, 1998 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During his tenure as Director, he fought syphilis,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stolberg |first=Sheryl Gay |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/10/08/us/us-says-stars-are-aligned-to-vanquish-an-old-foe-syphilis.html |title=U.S. Says 'Stars Are Aligned' to Vanquish an Old Foe: Syphilis |date=October 8, 1999 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and supervised the investigation into the [[2001 anthrax attacks]];<ref>{{Cite news |last=Altman |first=Lawrence K. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/13/science/the-doctor-s-world-when-everything-changed-at-the-cdc.html |title=THE DOCTOR'S WORLD; When Everything Changed at the C.D.C. |date=November 13, 2001 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=|language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> before leaving the agency in March 2002.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pear |first=Robert |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/22/us/embattled-disease-agency-chief-is-quitting.html |title=Embattled Disease Agency Chief Is Quitting |date=February 22, 2002 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nKoplan earned a bachelor's degree in English from [[Yale University]], a master's degree in public health from [[Harvard University]] and a medical doctorate from the [[Mt. Sinai School of Medicine]].<ref name=\"Epi\">{{cite news |last1=McClam |first1=Erin |title=CDC Chief Jeffrey Koplan Resigns |url=https://www.ph.ucla.edu/epi/bioter/koplanresigns.html |accessdate=16 April 2020 |publisher=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[David Satcher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = Director of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|years=1998-2002}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Julie Gerberding]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koplan, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:Directors of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]\n[[Category:Yale College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard School of Public Health alumni]]\n[[Category:Mount Sinai School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Emory University faculty]]\n[[Category:Centers for Disease Control and Prevention people]]\n[[Category:People from Boston]]\n\n\n{{US-med-bio-stub}}\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Javert2113", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing tag.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Koplan"}
{"title_page": "Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek", "text_new": "{{Expand Czech|date=April 2020|Komorn\u00ed_Hr\u00e1dek_(z\u00e1mek)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name          =  Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        =Village\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek castle.jpg\n|imagesize              =\n|image_caption          = Aerial view of the Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek chateau and surrounding land\n|image_flag             =\n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             =\n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           =\n|shield_size            =\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                =\n|image_map1             =\n|mapsize1               =\n|map_caption            = Location of the town\n|pushpin_map            = Czech Republic\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in the Czech Republic\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Czech Republic}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Central Bohemian Region]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Bene\u0161ov District]]\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      =\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         =\n|unit_pref                =Imperial <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 6.69\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_metro_km2           =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = 2011\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 101\n|population_density_km2         =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset             =+1\n|timezone_DST         = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST         =+2\n|coordinates            = {{coord|49|51|1|N|14|47|56|E}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            = 257 24\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n[[File:Burg Kammerburg Kau\u0159zimer Kreises nach Sikora gemahlt von Joann. Venuto 1821.jpg|thumb|Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek, as painted by [[Joann Venuto]] in 1821]]\n\n'''Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek''' is a small village within the municipality of [[Chocerady]] in the [[Bene\u0161ov District]] of the [[Czech Republic]].\n\n==History== \nThe first written mention of the village dates back to 1401.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ruzkova |first1=Jirina |last2=Skrabal |first2=Josef |title=Historick\u00fd lexikon obc\u00ed \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky 1869\u20132005 |date=December 31, 2004 |publisher=\u010cesk\u00fd statistick\u00fd \u00fa\u0159ad |location=Prague |isbn=80-250-1310-3 |url=https://www.czso.cz/csu/czso/historicky-lexikon-obci-ceske-republiky-2001-877ljn6lu9 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |chapter=Part 1}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n\n===\u010cejchanov===\n{{ill|\u010cejchanov|cs}} is a ruined castle built before 1356. The castle was besieged and destroyed in 1404 by [[Zbyn\u011bk Zaj\u00edc of Hazmburk]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Durd\u00edk |first1=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Ilustrovan\u00e1 encyklopedie \u010desk\u00fdch hrad\u016f |date=2002 |publisher=Libri |location=Prague |isbn=80-7277-003-9 |pages=207}}</ref> It has been a protected cultural monument since 1965.<ref>''[[:cs:\u00dast\u0159edn\u00ed seznam kulturn\u00edch pam\u00e1tek \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky|Central List of Cultural Monuments of the Czech Republic]]''. Prague: National Heritage Institute [cit. 2019-07-16]. Record ID 142214: Hrad \u010cejchan\u016fv Hr\u00e1dek, z\u0159\u00edcenina a archeologick\u00e9 stopy. [https://pamatkovykatalog.cz/hrad-cejchanuv-hradek-zricenina-a-archeologicke-stopy-2152388 Historical catalog.]</ref>\n\n===Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek===\nKomorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek is home to a [[chateau]] of the same name. Originally, a castle was built by [[Racek Kobyla of Dvorce]] as permitted by King [[Wenceslas IV]] on August 28, 1412. The castle was likely the replacement for the older \u010cejchanov (see above), only 200 meters to the west.<ref name=durdik2>{{cite book |last1=Durd\u00edk |first1=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Ilustrovan\u00e1 encyklopedie \u010desk\u00fdch hrad\u016f |date=2002 |publisher=Libri |location=Prague |isbn=80-7277-003-9 |pages=268\u2013269}}</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Racek Kobyla in 1416, his widow ceded the castle to the [[Hussite]] nobleman {{ill|William Kostka of Postupice|cs|Vil\u00e9m_Kostka_z_Postupic}} in 1422.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=\u0160imek |editor1-first=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Hrady, z\u00e1mky a tvrze v \u010cech\u00e1ch, na Morav\u011b a ve Slezsku |date=1985 |publisher=Nakladatelstv\u00ed Svoboda|url=https://www.academia.edu/30690183/Tom%C3%A1%C5%A1_%C5%A0imek_a_kol._Hrady_z%C3%A1mky_a_tvrze_v_%C4%8Cech%C3%A1ch_na_Morav%C4%9B_a_ve_Slezsku_Kniha_6_-_V%C3%BDchodn%C3%AD_%C4%8Cechy_Castles_and_fortresses_in_Bohemia_Moravia_and_Silesia_Book_6_-_East_Bohemia_ |location=Prague |pages=202\u2013203}}</ref>\n\nOriginally constructed as a [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] castle complete with tower and moat, it was redesigned in the 16th century as a [[Renaissance]] chateau. Some of the original masonry survives on the southern and western sides.<ref name=durdik2/> Three additional [[Wing (building)|wings]] were added during the 17th century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poche |first1=Emanuel |title=Um\u011bleck\u00e9 pam\u00e1tky \u010cech |volume=1|date=1977 |publisher=Academia |page=510 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Um%C4%9Bleck%C3%A9_pam%C3%A1tky_%C4%8Cech/CSufvwEACAAJ |language=cs}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*''This article was initially translated from the Czech Wikipedia.''\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Bene\u0161ov District]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in the Czech Republic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Czech|date=April 2020|Komorn\u00ed_Hr\u00e1dek_(z\u00e1mek)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name          =  Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        =Village\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek castle.jpg\n|imagesize              =\n|image_caption          = Aerial view of the Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek chateau and surrounding land\n|image_flag             =\n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             =\n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           =\n|shield_size            =\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                =\n|image_map1             =\n|mapsize1               =\n|map_caption            = Location of the town\n|pushpin_map            = Czech Republic\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in the Czech Republic\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Czech Republic}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Central Bohemian Region]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Bene\u0161ov District]]\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      =\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         =\n|unit_pref                =Imperial <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 6.69\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_metro_km2           =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = 2011\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 101\n|population_density_km2         =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset             =+1\n|timezone_DST         = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST         =+2\n|coordinates            = {{coord|49|51|1|N|14|47|56|E}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            = 257 24\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n[[File:Burg Kammerburg Kau\u0159zimer Kreises nach Sikora gemahlt von Joann. Venuto 1821.jpg|thumb|Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek, as painted by [[Joann Venuto]] in 1821]]\n\n'''Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek''' is a small village within the municipality of [[Chocerady]] in the [[Bene\u0161ov District]] of the [[Czech Republic]].\n\n==History== \nThe first written mention of the village dates back to 1401.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ruzkova |first1=Jirina |last2=Skrabal |first2=Josef |title=Historick\u00fd lexikon obc\u00ed \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky 1869-2005 |date=December 31, 2004 |publisher=\u010cesk\u00fd statistick\u00fd \u00fa\u0159ad |location=Prague |isbn=80-250-1310-3 |url=https://www.czso.cz/csu/czso/historicky-lexikon-obci-ceske-republiky-2001-877ljn6lu9 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |chapter=Part 1}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n\n===\u010cejchanov===\n{{ill|\u010cejchanov|cs}} is a ruined castle built before 1356. The castle was besieged and destroyed in 1404 by [[Zbyn\u011bk Zaj\u00edc of Hazmburk]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Durd\u00edk |first1=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Ilustrovan\u00e1 encyklopedie \u010desk\u00fdch hrad\u016f |date=2002 |publisher=Libri |location=Prague |isbn=80-7277-003-9 |pages=207}}</ref> It has been a protected cultural monument since 1965.<ref>''[[:cs:\u00dast\u0159edn\u00ed seznam kulturn\u00edch pam\u00e1tek \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky|Central List of Cultural Monuments of the Czech Republic]]''. Prague: National Heritage Institute [cit. 2019-07-16]. Record ID 142214: Hrad \u010cejchan\u016fv Hr\u00e1dek, z\u0159\u00edcenina a archeologick\u00e9 stopy. [https://pamatkovykatalog.cz/hrad-cejchanuv-hradek-zricenina-a-archeologicke-stopy-2152388 Historical catalog.]</ref>\n\n===Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek===\nKomorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek is home to a [[chateau]] of the same name. Originally, a castle was built by [[Racek Kobyla of Dvorce]] as permitted by King [[Wenceslas IV]] on August 28, 1412. The castle was likely the replacement for the older \u010cejchanov (see above), only 200 meters to the west.<ref name=durdik2>{{cite book |last1=Durd\u00edk |first1=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Ilustrovan\u00e1 encyklopedie \u010desk\u00fdch hrad\u016f |date=2002 |publisher=Libri |location=Prague |isbn=80-7277-003-9 |pages=268\u2013269}}</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Racek Kobyla in 1416, his widow ceded the castle to the [[Hussite]] nobleman {{ill|William Kostka of Postupice|cs|Vil\u00e9m_Kostka_z_Postupic}} in 1422.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=\u0160imek |editor1-first=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |title=Hrady, z\u00e1mky a tvrze v \u010cech\u00e1ch, na Morav\u011b a ve Slezsku |date=1985 |publisher=Nakladatelstv\u00ed Svoboda|url=https://www.academia.edu/30690183/Tom%C3%A1%C5%A1_%C5%A0imek_a_kol._Hrady_z%C3%A1mky_a_tvrze_v_%C4%8Cech%C3%A1ch_na_Morav%C4%9B_a_ve_Slezsku_Kniha_6_-_V%C3%BDchodn%C3%AD_%C4%8Cechy_Castles_and_fortresses_in_Bohemia_Moravia_and_Silesia_Book_6_-_East_Bohemia_ |location=Prague |pages=202\u2013203}}</ref>\n\nOriginally constructed as a [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] castle complete with tower and moat, it was redesigned in the 16th century as a [[Renaissance]] chateau. Some of the original masonry survives on the southern and western sides.<ref name=durdik2/> Three additional [[Wing (building)|wings]] were added during the 17th century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poche |first1=Emanuel |title=Um\u011bleck\u00e9 pam\u00e1tky \u010cech |volume=1|date=1977 |publisher=Academia |page=510 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Um%C4%9Bleck%C3%A9_pam%C3%A1tky_%C4%8Cech/CSufvwEACAAJ |language=cs}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*''This article was initially translated from the Czech Wikipedia.''\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Komorn\u00ed Hr\u00e1dek}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Bene\u0161ov District]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in the Czech Republic]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:replaced: 1869-2005 \u2192 1869\u20132005", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Komorn%C3%AD_Hr%C3%A1dek"}
{"title_page": "The Flintstone Comedy Show", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Flintstone Comedy Show\n| image                = Hanna-Barbera 0016.jpg\n| genre                = [[Animation]], [[Comedy]]\n| camera               =\n| picture_format       =\n| runtime              = 90 minutes (1980\u201381)<br>60 minutes (1981)\n| creator              =\n| writer               = \n| director             = [[Ray Patterson (animator)|Ray Patterson]]<br>[[George Gordon (animator)|George Gordon]]<br>[[Rudy Zamora]]\n| producer             = [[Alex Lovy]]<br>[[Carl Urbano]]\n| executive_producer   = [[William Hanna]]<br>[[Joseph Barbera]]\n| composer             = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| starring             =\n| voices               = [[Gay Autterson]]<br>[[Mel Blanc]]<br>[[Henry Corden]]<br>[[Ruta Lee]]<br>[[Kenneth Mars]]<br>[[Mitzi McCall]]<br>[[Don Messick]]<br>[[Charles Nelson Reilly]]<br>[[Paul Reubens]]<br>[[Zelda Rubinstein]]<br>[[Michael Sheehan (actor)|Michael Sheehan]]<br>[[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]]<br>[[Russi Taylor]]<br>[[Jean Vander Pyl]]<br>[[Lennie Weinrib]]<br>[[Frank Welker]]\n| narrated             = [[Kenneth Mars]] (\"Captain Caveman\" segments)\n| theme_music_composer = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| company              = [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]]\n| distributor = [[Turner Program Services]] (1992\u201396){{Plainlist}}[[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]] (1996\u2013present)\n| opentheme            =\n| endtheme             =\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| network              = [[NBC]]\n| audio_format         = [[Monaural]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1980|11|22}}\n| last_aired           = {{end date|1981|10|24}}\n| num_seasons          = 2\n| num_episodes         = 18\n| list_episodes        =\n| preceded_by          = ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]''\n| followed_by          = ''[[The Flintstone Funnies]]''\n| related              =\n| website              =\n}}\n'''''The Flintstone Comedy Show''''' (not to be confused with the shortened, re-titled 1973 version of CBS's ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'') is an American [[Saturday-morning cartoon|animated television series]] revival and [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[The Flintstones]]'' produced by [[Hanna-Barbera]] which aired on [[NBC]] from November 22, 1980  to October 24, 1981.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=209-214}}</ref> Outside [[North America]], the show was released under title of ''Flintstone Frolics''. The show contained six segments: ''The Flintstone Family Adventures'', ''Bedrock Cops'', ''Pebbles, Dino and Bamm-Bamm'', ''Captain Caveman'', ''Dino and Cavemouse'' and ''The Frankenstones''.<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981 |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/page/106/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |pages=106-109}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe series featured new characters ([[The Frankenstones]], Cavemouse) as well as older characters (Penny, Wiggy, Moonrock and Schleprock of 1971's ''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]'' and 1972's ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]'' on [[CBS]], [[Al Capp]]'s the [[Shmoo]] from his show ''[[The New Shmoo]]'' which also aired on [[NBC]] in 1979, [[Captain Caveman and the Teen Angels|Captain Caveman]] from his own series on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in 1977 which lasted 3 seasons).\n\nA series of gags, educational spots, games, how-to-draw and a dance-of-the-week were featured in-between the six segments every week. In [[1982 in television|1982]], reruns of the show were repackaged for two seasons under the title '''''[[The Flintstone Funnies]]'''''. Reruns of \"Dino and Cavemouse\" aired on the [[Disney Channel]] adaption of ''[[Wake, Rattle, and Roll]]''.\n\n==The Flintstone Family Adventures==\nThis segment featured the traditional antics and adventures of The Flintstones and The Rubbles.\n\n====Season 1 (1980\u201381)====\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#FF681F; width:20px\"| {{Abbr|N\u00ba|Number}}\n! style=\"background:#FF681F; width:20px\"| {{Abbr|Ep|Episode}}\n! style=\"background:#FF681F\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#FF681F; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 1\n| Title               = R.V. Fever\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|1980|11|22}}\n| ShortSummary        = As the Flintstones and the Rubbles take a road trip, the R.V. trailer with Fred and Barney comes unhitched.\n| LineColor           = #FF681F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 2\n| Title               = Sands of the Saharastone\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|1980|11|29}}\n| ShortSummary        = The Flintstones and the Rubbles take a trip to Algeristone where Wilma and Betty are abducted by sheiks to add to their harems.\n| LineColor           = #FF681F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 3\n| Title               = Gold Fever\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|1980|12|6}}\n| ShortSummary        = Fred and Barney go on a trip to the Bedrock Mountains to search for gold until some claim jumpers try to capture them.\n| LineColor           = #FF681F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 4\n| Title               = Bogged Down\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|1980|12|13}}\n| ShortSummary        = After Barney sells a dilapidated resort that he inherited from his uncle, Fred discovers oil on the property.\n| LineColor           = #FF681F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 5\n|