{"title_page": "Gornje Obrinje massacre", "text_new": "{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title= Gornje Obrinje massacre\n|image=\n|caption=\n|location= Gornje Obrinje, [[AP Kosovo and Metohija]], [[FR Yugoslavia]]\n|target= [[Kosovo Albanians]]\n|date= 26 September 1998\n|time= \n|timezone= \n|type= Mass killing\n|fatalities=21\n|perps= Serbian police\n|motive=Retribution\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Kosovo War}}\nThe '''Gornje Obrinje massacre''' ({{lang-sq|Masakra n\u00eb Abri t\u00eb Ep\u00ebrme}}, {{lang-sr|Masakr u Gornjem Obrinju}}) refers to the killing of 21 [[Kosovo Albanians]], belonging to the same family, in a forest outside the village of Donje Obrinje on 26 September 1998 during the [[Kosovo War]]. Among the victims were women and children. <!-- Hysenaj compound victims needs to be added if larger scope, as per Bouckaert -->\n\nThe Yugoslav Army had been deployed in the area for several months in a major offensive against the [[Kosovo Liberation Army]] (KLA), which had assumed loose control of an estimated one-third of the province. There was serious combat in the areas of [[Suva Reka]] and [[Drenica]].<ref name=HRW1999>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1999/kosovo/index.htm|author=Human Rights Watch|title=Federal Republic of Yugoslavia: A Week of Terror in Drenica, Humanitarian Law Violations in Kosovo|year=1999}}</ref> At least 14 policemen had been killed by the KLA earlier that month.<ref name=\"Henriksen2013\">{{cite book|author=Dag Henriksen|title=NATO's Gamble: Combining Diplomacy and Airpower in the Kosovo Crisis, 1998-1999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B61kAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT132|date=15 November 2013|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-61251-555-7|pages=132\u2013}}</ref> On 25 September, a Serbian police vehicle was blown up by a detonation on the road between Likovac and Gornje Obrinje, with five dead.<ref name=\"Mines1999\">{{cite book|author=International Campaign to Ban Land Mines|title=Landmine Monitor Report 1999: Toward a Mine-free World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiwJHi8Pa2IC&pg=PA831|year=1999|publisher=Human Rights Watch|isbn=978-1-56432-231-9|pages=831\u2013}}</ref> The KLA sometimes retreated through villages after their frequent attacks on Serbian police, moving in proximity to civilians.<ref name=\"Abrahams2015\">{{cite book|author=Fred C. Abrahams|title=Modern Albania: From Dictatorship to Democracy in Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7KMHCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA264|date=15 May 2015|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-1-4798-9668-4|pages=264\u2013}}</ref> According to [[HRW]], the Serbian special police retaliated by killing 21 civilians,<ref name=\"Henriksen2013\"/> belonging to the family of Deliaj from Donje Obrinje, on 26 September.{{sfn|HRW|1998}} Among these were 9 women and 5 children.<ref name=\"UdovickiRidgeway2000\">{{cite book|author1=Jasminka Udovicki|author2=James Ridgeway|title=Burn This House: The Making and Unmaking of Yugoslavia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DHMioF8-CewC&pg=PA331|date=10 October 2000|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0-8223-8091-9|pages=331\u2013}}</ref> They had been executed in a nearby forest.{{sfn|HRW|1998}} Later that same day, 14 men were randomly selected some kilometres from Gornje Obrinje, abused for several hours, then eventually 13 were executed<ref name=\"Henriksen2013\"/> in Golubovac.<ref name=HRW1999/> On 27 September HRW researchers and journalists arrived at the village and documented the massacre, garnering major Western media coverage.<ref name=HRW1999/>\n\nInternational political pressure on the [[Government of Serbia and Montenegro|FR Yugoslav government]] to end its crackdown in Kosovo was accelerated by the news of these killings, leading to a [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1203|new resolution]] issued by the [[United Nations Security Council]] on 24 October 1998, calling for the deployment of the Diplomatic Verification Mission and an end to hostilities.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kosovo War]]\n* [[War crimes in the Kosovo War]]\n* [[List of massacres in the Kosovo War]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book| last=Krieger| first=Heike| ref=Krieger| year=2001| publisher=Cambridge University Press|  url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-OhPTJn8ZWoC| title=The Kosovo Conflict and International Law: An Analytical Documentation 1974-1999| accessdate=27 February 2013| isbn=9780521800716}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bahador|first=B.|title=The CNN Effect in Action: How the News Media Pushed the West toward War in Kosovo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DjeDDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|year=2007|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-0-230-60422-3|pages=83\u201384}}\n* {{cite web|author=HRW|year=1998|title=Eighteen Civilians Massacred in Kosovo Forest|publisher=HRW|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/1998/09/28/eighteen-civilians-massacred-kosovo-forest|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Peter Bouckaert|author2=Fred Abrahams|author3=Human Rights Watch (Organization)|title=Federal Republic of Yugoslavia: A Week of Terror in Drenica : Humanitarian Law Violations in Kosovo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ozTFV4ddD9cC&pg=PA20|year=1999|publisher=Human Rights Watch|isbn=978-1-56432-227-2|pages=20\u2013}}\n* {{cite web|title=Da znamo: Gornje Obrinje, 26. septembar 1998.|publisher=HLC-RDC|url=http://www.hlc-rdc.org/?p=13076}}\n\n[[Category:Serbian war crimes in the Kosovo War]]\n[[Category:Massacres in the Kosovo War]]\n[[Category:1998 in Kosovo]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1998]]\n[[Category:Anti-Albanian sentiment]]\n[[Category:September 1998 events in Europe]]\n{{coord|42|38|N|20|45|E|display=title}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title= Gornje Obrinje massacre\n|image=\n|caption=\n|location= Gornje Obrinje, [[AP Kosovo and Metohija]], [[FR Yugoslavia]]\n|target= [[Kosovo Albanians]]\n|date= 26 September 1998\n|time= \n|timezone= \n|type= Mass killing\n|fatalities=21\n|perps= Serbian police\n|motive=Retribution\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Kosovo War}}\nThe '''Gornje Obrinje massacre''' ({{lang-sq|Masakra n\u00eb Abri t\u00eb Ep\u00ebrme}}, {{lang-sr|Masakr u Gornjem Obrinju}}) refers to the killing of 21 [[Kosovo Albanians]], belonging to the same family, in a forest outside the village of Donje Obrinje on 26 September 1998 during the [[Kosovo War]]. Among the victims were women and children. <!-- Hysenaj compound victims needs to be added if larger scope, as per Bouckaert -->\n\nThe Yugoslav Army had been deployed in the area for several months in a major offensive against the [[Kosovo Liberation Army]] (KLA), which had assumed loose control of an estimated one-third of the province. There was serious combat in the areas of [[Suva Reka]] and [[Drenica]].<ref name=HRW1999>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1999/kosovo/index.htm|author=Human Rights Watch|title=Federal Republic of Yugoslavia: A Week of Terror in Drenica, Humanitarian Law Violations in Kosovo|year=1999}}</ref> At least 14 policemen had been killed by the KLA earlier that month.<ref name=\"Henriksen2013\">{{cite book|author=Dag Henriksen|title=NATO's Gamble: Combining Diplomacy and Airpower in the Kosovo Crisis, 1998-1999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B61kAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT132|date=15 November 2013|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-61251-555-7|pages=132\u2013}}</ref> On 25 September, a Serbian police vehicle was blown up by a detonation on the road between Likovac and Gornje Obrinje, with five dead.<ref name=\"Mines1999\">{{cite book|author=International Campaign to Ban Land Mines|title=Landmine Monitor Report 1999: Toward a Mine-free World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiwJHi8Pa2IC&pg=PA831|year=1999|publisher=Human Rights Watch|isbn=978-1-56432-231-9|pages=831\u2013}}</ref> The KLA retreated through villages after their frequent attacks on Serbian police, exposing civilians, in order to get Western attention and support with civilian deaths.<ref name=\"Abrahams2015\">{{cite book|author=Fred C. Abrahams|title=Modern Albania: From Dictatorship to Democracy in Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7KMHCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA264|date=15 May 2015|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-1-4798-9668-4|pages=264\u2013}}</ref> According to [[HRW]], the Serbian special police retaliated by killing 21 civilians,<ref name=\"Henriksen2013\"/> belonging to the family of Deliaj from Donje Obrinje, on 26 September.{{sfn|HRW|1998}} Among these were 9 women and 5 children.<ref name=\"UdovickiRidgeway2000\">{{cite book|author1=Jasminka Udovicki|author2=James Ridgeway|title=Burn This House: The Making and Unmaking of Yugoslavia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DHMioF8-CewC&pg=PA331|date=10 October 2000|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0-8223-8091-9|pages=331\u2013}}</ref> They had been executed in a nearby forest.{{sfn|HRW|1998}} Later that same day, 14 men were randomly selected some kilometres from Gornje Obrinje, abused for several hours, then eventually 13 were executed<ref name=\"Henriksen2013\"/> in Golubovac.<ref name=HRW1999/> On 27 September HRW researchers and journalists arrived at the village and documented the massacre, garnering major Western media coverage.<ref name=HRW1999/>\n\nInternational political pressure on the [[Government of Serbia and Montenegro|FR Yugoslav government]] to end its crackdown in Kosovo was accelerated by the news of these killings, leading to a [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1203|new resolution]] issued by the [[United Nations Security Council]] on 24 October 1998, calling for the deployment of the Diplomatic Verification Mission and an end to hostilities.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kosovo War]]\n* [[War crimes in the Kosovo War]]\n* [[List of massacres in the Kosovo War]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book| last=Krieger| first=Heike| ref=Krieger| year=2001| publisher=Cambridge University Press|  url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-OhPTJn8ZWoC| title=The Kosovo Conflict and International Law: An Analytical Documentation 1974-1999| accessdate=27 February 2013| isbn=9780521800716}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bahador|first=B.|title=The CNN Effect in Action: How the News Media Pushed the West toward War in Kosovo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DjeDDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|year=2007|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-0-230-60422-3|pages=83\u201384}}\n* {{cite web|author=HRW|year=1998|title=Eighteen Civilians Massacred in Kosovo Forest|publisher=HRW|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/1998/09/28/eighteen-civilians-massacred-kosovo-forest|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Peter Bouckaert|author2=Fred Abrahams|author3=Human Rights Watch (Organization)|title=Federal Republic of Yugoslavia: A Week of Terror in Drenica : Humanitarian Law Violations in Kosovo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ozTFV4ddD9cC&pg=PA20|year=1999|publisher=Human Rights Watch|isbn=978-1-56432-227-2|pages=20\u2013}}\n* {{cite web|title=Da znamo: Gornje Obrinje, 26. septembar 1998.|publisher=HLC-RDC|url=http://www.hlc-rdc.org/?p=13076}}\n\n[[Category:Serbian war crimes in the Kosovo War]]\n[[Category:Massacres in the Kosovo War]]\n[[Category:1998 in Kosovo]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1998]]\n[[Category:Anti-Albanian sentiment]]\n[[Category:September 1998 events in Europe]]\n{{coord|42|38|N|20|45|E|display=title}}\n", "name_user": "Mozad655", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed language to more neutral and less presumptuous.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gornje_Obrinje_massacre"}
{"title_page": "Heosphora grammivena", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| taxon = Heosphora grammivena\n| authority = [[George Hampson|Hampson]], 1918\n| synonyms = *''Saluria grammivena'' <small>Hampson, 1918</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Heosphora grammivena''''' is a species of [[moth]] in the family [[Pyralidae]]. The species was first described by [[George Hampson]] in 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/data/lepindex/detail/?taxonno=8221&page_no=1&page_size=30|title=LepIndex \u2013 grammivena|website=www.nhm.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biolib.cz/en/taxon/id1101614/|title=BioLib: Biological library|last=ondrej.zicha(at)gmail.com|first=Ondrej Zicha;|website=www.biolib.cz|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:fe70e4ac-11bf-4689-a7af-33d5a847652a|title=Species: Heosphora grammivena|last=Australia|first=Atlas of Living|website=bie.ala.org.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Pyralidae]]\n\n\n{{Pyralidae-stub}}\n[[Category:Moths of Australia]]\n[[Category:Moths described in 1918]]\n[[Category:Taxa described by George Hampson]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| taxon = Heosphora grammivena\n| authority = [[George Hampson|Hampson]], 1918\n| synonyms = *''Saluria grammivena'' <small>Hampson, 1918</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Heosphora grammivena''''' is a species of [[moth]] in the family [[Pyralidae]]. The species was first described by [[George Hampson]] in 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/data/lepindex/detail/?taxonno=8221&page_no=1&page_size=30|title=LepIndex - grammivena|website=www.nhm.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biolib.cz/en/taxon/id1101614/|title=BioLib: Biological library|last=ondrej.zicha(at)gmail.com|first=Ondrej Zicha;|website=www.biolib.cz|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:fe70e4ac-11bf-4689-a7af-33d5a847652a|title=Species: Heosphora grammivena|last=Australia|first=Atlas of Living|website=bie.ala.org.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Pyralidae]]\n\n\n{{Pyralidae-stub}}\n[[Category:Moths of Australia]]\n[[Category:Moths described in 1918]]\n[[Category:Taxa described by George Hampson]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: -  \u2192  \u2013", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heosphora_grammivena"}
{"title_page": "Piers Morgan", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Piers Morgan\n| image              = Piers Morgan at PaleyFest 2013.jpg\n| caption            = Morgan at PaleyFest 2013\n| birth_name         = Piers Stefan O'Meara\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1965|03|30}}\n| birth_place        = [[Newick]], East Sussex, England\n| television         = {{Flat list|\n* ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]''\n* ''[[America's Got Talent]]''\n* ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 7)|The Celebrity Apprentice]]''\n* ''[[The Dark Side of Fame with Piers Morgan]]''\n* ''[[Piers Morgan On...]]''\n* ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]''\n* ''[[Piers Morgan Live]]''\n* ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''\n}}\n| education          = [[Chailey School]]<br/>[[Priory School, Lewes]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Harlow College]]\n| nationality        = English \n| employer         = {{Flat list|\n* ''South London News'' (1985\u201388)\n* ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' (1989\u20131994)\n* ''[[News of the World]]'' (1994\u201395)\n* ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' (1995\u20132004)\n}}\n| occupation         = {{Flat list|\n* Television presenter\n* writer\n* [[Citizen journalism|journalist]]\n* columnist\n* [[Social criticism|social critic]]\n}}\n| years_active       = 1985\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Marion Shalloe|1991|2008|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Celia Walden]]<br>|24 June 2010}}\n| party              = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Piers Stefan Pughe-Morgan'''  ({{IPAc-en|p|\u026a\u0259r|s}}; [[Given name#Name at birth|n\u00e9]] '''O'Meara'''; born 30 March 1965) is an English broadcaster, journalist, writer, and television personality. He is currently a co-presenter of the [[ITV Breakfast]] programme ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' from Monday to Wednesday each week.\n\nMorgan began his career in [[Fleet Street]] as a writer and editor for several [[tabloid journalism|tabloid]] papers, including ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', ''[[News of the World]]'', and the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''. In 1994, aged 29, he was appointed editor of the ''News of the World'' by [[Rupert Murdoch]], which made him the youngest editor of a British national newspaper in more than half a century.<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> On television, he hosted ''[[Piers Morgan Live]]'' on [[CNN]] from 2011 to 2014, replacing ''[[Larry King Live]]'' in the timeslot following [[Larry King|King]]'s retirement.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100911024937/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/39060518/ns/today-entertainment \"Piers Morgan is Larry King's CNN replacement\"], MSNBC, 8 September 2010. Retrieved 7 February 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Piers Morgan's CNN show cancelled after 3 years|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/piers-morgan-s-cnn-show-cancelled-after-3-years-1.2548831|accessdate=24 February 2014|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=23 February 2014}}</ref> He was a judge on ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' and ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nudd|first=Tim|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20544255,00.html|title=Piers Morgan Leaving America's Got Talent|newspaper=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref> In 2008, Morgan won the seventh season of the US ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. Season 7)|Celebrity Apprentice]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Caitlin |date=28 March 2008 |title=Relative unknown wins 'Celebrity Apprentice' |url=http://www.today.com/id/23838097/ns/today-entertainment/t/relative-unknown-wins-celebrity-apprentice |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref> In the UK, he has presented ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]'' since 2009, and ''Good Morning Britain'' since 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|work=The Guardian|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=14 October 2015|title=Piers Morgan handed permanent role on Good Morning Britain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/oct/13/piers-morgan-permanent-fixture-good-morning-britain}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/08/01/piers-morgan-has-been-replaced-on-good-morning-britain/1/?tse_id=INF_6f69916076e411e785e8bfcdfe5d7856|title=Piers Morgan has been replaced on Good Morning Britain|work=PinkNews|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref> Morgan has written eight books, including four volumes of memoirs.\n\nWhile working at ''Daily Mirror'', he was in charge during the period that the paper was implicated in the [[News International phone hacking scandal|phone hacking scandal]]. In 2011, Morgan denied having ever hacked a phone or \"to my knowledge published any story obtained from the hacking of a phone\". In 2012, he was criticised in the findings of the [[Leveson Inquiry]] by chair [[Brian Leveson]] who stated that comments made in Morgan's testimony about phone hacking were \"utterly unpersuasive\" and \"that he was aware that it was taking place in the press as a whole and that he was sufficiently unembarrassed by what was criminal behaviour that he was prepared to joke about it\".<ref name=\"Mark Sweney\">{{cite news |last=Sweney |first=Mark |date=30 November 2012 |title=Piers Morgan claims over phone hacking branded 'utterly unpersuasive' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/nov/30/piers-morgan-phone-hacking-leveson-inquiry |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPiers Morgan was born in 1965 in [[Surrey]], England (although he moved to [[Newick]], Sussex, England after a few months<ref name=\"offaly\"/>) as Piers Stefan O'Meara, the son of Vincent Eamonn O'Meara, an Irish dentist originally from [[County Offaly]],<ref name=\"offaly\">[http://www.offalyindependent.ie/news/roundup/articles/2011/01/21/4002777-first-barack-now-piers-morgan-is-offaly-conquering Piers Morgan reference to his father's background], Offalyindependent.ie (cached), 21 January 2011. Retrieved 7 February 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/44111/pages/10035|title=Notices Under The Trustee Act, 1925|work=The London Gazette|date=13 September 1966|page=67}}</ref> and Gabrielle Georgina Sybille (n\u00e9e Oliver),<ref name=cantoph>{{cite web|url=http://website.lineone.net/~hstjw/p29.htm#i1071|first=Hugh|last=Wilding|title=Wildings & Thurleys, Cantophers & McConnells|year=2008}}</ref> who raised her son as a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref name=cantoph /> With regard to his religious views, Morgan still identifies as a Catholic due to his mother's influence, and believes in an [[afterlife]], but does not \"go to [[Sacrament of Penance|Confession]], probably because it would take me too long\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mance |first1=Henry |title=Piers Morgan on Trump, Twitter and the power of prayer |url=https://www.ft.com/content/eac296be-03fc-11e7-ace0-1ce02ef0def9 |accessdate=30 July 2018 |work=Financial Times |date=15 March 2017}}</ref> He has a brother, Jeremy, who is two years older.<ref name=\"Naughton\"/>\n\nHis father died when Morgan was 11 months old; his mother later married Glynne Pughe-Morgan,<ref>Piers Morgan, The Hot Seat: Love, War, and Cable News (2014), p. 5</ref><ref>Roy Greenslade, Press Gang: How Newspapers Make Profits from Propaganda (2004), p. 602</ref> a Welsh publican later in the meat distribution business, and he took his stepfather's surname.<ref name=\"Davies1994\">{{cite news |last=Davies |first=Hunter |author-link=Hunter Davies |date=13 December 1994 |title=From City boy to World leader |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/from-city-boy-to-world-leader-1387335.html |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> He was at the independent Cumnor House prep school <!-- boarded for two years. (Davies 1994) -->between the ages of seven and 13, then [[Chailey School]], a [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]] secondary school in [[Chailey]], near [[Lewes]], East Sussex. <!-- followed by [[Priory School, Lewes]], for the [[sixth form]]. --><ref name=\"Naughton\">{{Cite news|last1=Naughton|first1=Philippe|last2=Costello|first2=Miles|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/the-rhino-in-riot-gear-has-a-way-of-coaxing-out-secrets-3hvp7nw6kt2|title=The rhino in riot gear has a way of coaxing out secrets: PROFILE: Piers Morgan|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=6 April 2008|accessdate=16 July 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref> After nine months at [[Lloyd's of London]], Morgan studied journalism at [[Harlow College]].<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> Morgan joined the Surrey and South London Newspaper Group in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ortiz|first=Jen|title=SCANDALOUS! 11 Years in the Life of Piers Morgan|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/piers-morgan-hacking-murdoch-bio-2011-7|newspaper=Business Insider|accessdate=11 November 2011}}</ref> \n\n==Press career==\n===At the Murdoch titles===\nMorgan began to work as a freelance at ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' in 1988, at this point dropping his [[double-barrelled name]]. He told [[Hunter Davies]] in December 1994 that he was personally recruited by ''Sun'' editor [[Kelvin MacKenzie]] to work on the newspaper's show business column \"Bizarre\", his first high-profile post.<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> Although he was not a fan of pop music, he was considered skilled at self-publicity and became the column's main writer. \"I became the Friend of the Stars, a rampant egomaniac, pictured all the time with famous people \u2013 [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Sylvester Stallone|Stallone]], [[David Bowie|Bowie]], [[Paul McCartney]], hundreds of them. It was shameless, as they didn't know me from Adam\", he told Davies.<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/>\n\nMorgan left this post in 1995 shortly after publishing photographs of [[Victoria Aitken|Catherine Victoria Lockwood]], then wife of [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer|Charles, Earl Spencer]], leaving an addictive disorders clinic in Surrey.<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Rhys |date=12 May 1995 |title=Murdoch lashes editor shock |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/murdoch-lashes-editor-shock-1619121.html |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> This action ran against the editors' code of conduct,<ref name=\"BBC2004\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3713857.stm \"Profile: Piers Morgan\"], BBC News, 14 May 2004</ref> a misdemeanour for which the [[Press Complaints Commission]] upheld a complaint against Morgan.<ref name=\"BBC2004\"/> Murdoch was reported as having said that \"the boy went too far\"<ref>Ginny Dougary [http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/books/article2451447.ece \"Educating Piers\"], ''The Times Magazine'', 7 April 2007. {{subscription}}</ref> and publicly distanced himself from the story.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/47847.stm \"Earl Spencer loses privacy battle to Europe\"], BBC News, 16 January 1998</ref> Fearful of a privacy law action if he had not criticised one of his employees, Murdoch is said to have apologised to Morgan in private.<ref>Tom Watson and Martin Hickman [https://books.google.com/books?id=Lel9DjaPgqEC&pg=PT30 ''Dial M for Murdoch: News Corporation and the Corruption of Britain''], London: Penguin, 2012, p. 30</ref><ref>Benjamin Wallace [http://nymag.com/news/media/piers-morgan-2011-10/index1.html \"Piers Morgan Isn\u2019t Sleeping Well\"], ''New York'' (magazine), 9 October 2011</ref>\n\nThe incident was reported to have contributed to Morgan's decision to leave for the ''Daily Mirror'' editorship.<ref name=\"Summerskill\">{{cite news |last=Summerskill |first=Ben |author-link=Ben Summerskill |date=1 September 2002 |title=Has Piers now got news for Ian? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/sep/01/pressandpublishing.uknews |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Morgan's autobiography ''[[The Insider: The Private Diaries of a Scandalous Decade|The Insider]]'' states that he left the ''News of the World'' for the ''Mirror'' of his own choice. It asserts he was an admirer of former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] for most of her period of office, making the appointment surprising as the ''Mirror'' is a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]-supporting title.<ref name=\"Naughton\"/>\n\n===''Daily Mirror'' editor===\nAs editor of the ''Daily Mirror'', Morgan was forced to apologise on television for the headline (rendered in upper case) \"Achtung Surrender! For You Fritz Ze Euro Championship Is Over\" on 25 June 1996, a day before [[England national football team|England]] met [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in a semi-final of the [[1996 European Football Championship|Euro '96]] football championships.<ref>{{cite news |last=Maguire |first=Kevin |author-link=Kevin Maguire (journalist) |date=25 February 2002 |title=The New Statesman Profile \u2013 Piers Morgan |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/node/142285 |newspaper=[[New Statesman]] |location=London |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Byrne |first=Ciar |date=15 May 2004 |title=Piers Morgan: The man with no moral compass who found his destiny in a steadfast opposition to war |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/piers-morgan-the-man-with-no-moral-compass-who-found-his-destiny-in-a-steadfast-opposition-to-war-6169902.html |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref><ref>George Wilkes and Dominic Wing \"The British Press and European Integration: 1948 to 1996\", in David Baker, David Seawright (eds.) [https://books.google.com/books?id=MBKbtzPdbhQC&pg=PA202 ''Britain for and Against Europe: British Politics and the Question of European Integration''], Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1998, p. 202</ref><ref name=\"IHT\">{{Cite news |last=Thomsen |first=Ian |date=26 June 1996 |title=Oh, Sorry: Tabloids Lose the Soccer War |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/06/26/news/26iht-england.t_0.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=3 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nA\u00a316&nbsp;million package of investment in the title was rolled out from January, including the dropping of \"''Daily''\" from the masthead in February,<ref>Roy Greenslade ''Press Gang: How Newspapers Make Profits From Propaganda'', London: Pan, 2004 [2003], p. 657</ref> which was later reversed. [[Roy Greenslade]] wrote in August 1999 that Morgan's editorship \"has made a huge difference: his enormous enthusiasm, determination and focus is a major plus\".<ref>Roy Greenslade [https://www.theguardian.com/media/1999/aug/16/mondaymediasection.columnists \"Chasing the Sun's tail\"], ''The Guardian'', 16 August 1999</ref>\n\nMorgan was the subject of an investigation in 2000 after Suzy Jagger wrote an article for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' revealing that he had bought [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]20,000 worth of shares in the computer company [[Viglen]] soon before the ''Mirror'' 's \"City Slickers\" column tipped Viglen as a good buy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jagger |first=Suzy |title=Mirror editor saw his shares soar after paper tipped company |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/2000/02/02/nmir02.html |url-status=dead |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021122223139/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=%2Farchive%2F2000%2F02%2F02%2Fnmir02.html |archivedate=22 November 2002 |accessdate=13 January 2015 }}</ref> Morgan was found by the [[Press Complaints Commission]] to have breached the Code of Conduct on financial journalism, but kept his job. The \"City Slickers\" columnists, [[Anil Bhoyrul]] and [[James Hipwell]], were both found to have committed further breaches of the Code and were sacked before the inquiry concluded.<ref>{{cite news |last=Moyes |first=Jojo |author-link=Jojo Moyes |date=10 May 2000 |title=Columnist rewrites his 'Mirror' tips story over share tips |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/columnist-rewrites-his-mirror-tips-story-over-share-tips-279320.html |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Further enquiry by the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] in 2004 cleared Morgan of any charges.<ref name=\"cleared\">{{Cite news |title=Morgan cleared after shares probe |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3792225.stm |work=BBC News |date=10 June 2004}}</ref> On 7 December 2005, Bhoyrul and Hipwell were convicted of conspiracy to breach the Financial Services Act. During the trial it emerged that Morgan had bought \u00a367,000 worth of Viglen shares, emptying his bank account and investing under his (first) wife's name, too.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tryhorn |first=Chris  |date=23 November 2005 |title=Mirror editor 'bought \u00a367,000 of shares before they were tipped' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/nov/23/business.pressandpublishing |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Mirror'' attempted to move mid-market in 2002, eschewing the more trivial stories of show-business and gossip, but sales declined.<ref name=\"Naughton\"/><ref name=\"Barber\">{{cite news|last=Barber|first=Lynn|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/nov/20/newspaperformats.mirror|title=I should have been fired years ago, to be honest|work=The Observer|date=20 November 2005|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> In the wake of the [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse|Abu Ghraib torture scandal]], Morgan was sacked as editor of the ''Daily Mirror'' \"with immediate effect\" on 14 May 2004, after refusing to apologise to [[Sly Bailey]], then head of [[Trinity Mirror]], for authorising the newspaper's publication of photographs which had been shown to be false.<ref>Chris Tryhorn and Lisa O'Carroll [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2004/may/14/pressandpublishing.iraqandthemedia \"Morgan sacked from Daily Mirror\"], ''Media Guardian'', 14 May 2004</ref> These were alleged to show Iraqi prisoners being abused by [[British Army]] soldiers from the [[Queen's Lancashire Regiment]].<ref>{{Cite news\n |title=Daily Mirror statement in full \n |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html \n |publisher=CNN \n |date=13 May 2004 \n |accessdate=22 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041125053916/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html \n |archivedate=25 November 2004 |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> When, within days the photographs were shown to be crude fakes, under the headline \"SORRY..WE WERE HOAXED\", the ''Mirror'' responded that it had fallen victim to a \"calculated and malicious hoax\" and apologised for the publication of the photographs.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title       = Editor sacked over 'hoax' photos\n | url         = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/3716151.stm\n | publisher   = BBC News\n | date        = 14 May 2004\n | accessdate  = 27 December 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n | url         = http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/\n | title       = Fake abuse photos: Editor quits\n | publisher   = CNN\n | date        = 15 May 2004\n | archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20041012123314/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/\n | archivedate=12 October 2004}}</ref> However, Morgan has refused to admit that the photographs were faked, and has stated that the abuse shown in the photographs is similar to the sort of abuse which was happening in the British Army in Iraq at the time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Byers|first1=Dylan|title=Piers Morgan on phone-hacking, Iraq photos|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/01/piers-morgan-on-phone-hacking-iraq-photos-154551|accessdate=30 January 2018|work=Politico|date=18 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Post-''Mirror'' press career===\nIn partnership with [[Matthew Freud]], he gained ownership in May 2005 of ''[[Press Gazette]]'', a media trade publication together with its \"[[cash cow]]\", the [[British Press Awards]], in a deal worth \u00a31&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"pgdeal\">{{Cite news\n |first       = Jemima\n |last        = Kiss\n |title       = Piers Morgan clinches Press Gazette deal\n |url         = http://www.journalism.co.uk/2/articles/51408.php\n |publisher   = [[Journalism.co.uk]]\n |date        = 13 June 2005\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20091003002526/http://www.journalism.co.uk/2/articles/51408.php\n |archivedate = 3 October 2009\n|df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=\"prop\">{{Cite news\n | first       = Julia\n | last        = Day\n | title       = Piers Morgan turns proprietor with purchase of Press Gazette\n | url         = https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/may/28/pressandpublishing.uknews\n | newspaper   = The Guardian\n | date        = 28 May 2005\n | accessdate  = 22 May 2010\n}}</ref> This ownership was cited as one of the reasons many major newspapers boycotted the [[British Press Awards 2006#Controversy leading up to the 2006 awards|2006 awards]].<ref name=\"boyc\">{{Cite news\n | first       = Roy\n | last        = Greenslade\n | author-link = Roy Greenslade\n | title       = Big titles boycott Morgans organ press awards\n | url         = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2930708/Big-titles-boycott-Morgans-organ-press-awards.html\n | work   = The Daily Telegraph\n | date        = 24 January 2006\n | accessdate  = 22 May 2010\n}}</ref> ''Press Gazette'' entered [[administrative receivership]] toward the end of 2006,<ref>{{Cite news\n | first       = Roy\n | last        = Greenslade\n | title       = Press Gazette now in administration\n | url         = https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2006/nov/06/pressgazettenowinadministr\n | work   = The Guardian\n | date        = 6 November 2006\n | accessdate  = 27 December 2012\n}}</ref> before being sold to a trade buyer.\n\n''[[First News (newspaper)|First News]]'' was launched by Morgan on 4 May 2006. A weekly paper aimed at seven to 14-year-olds, he said at its launch that the paper was to be \"Britain's first national newspaper for children\".<ref>\"Britain's first national newspaper for children to launch Friday\", Associated Press, 4 May 2006</ref><ref>Other newspapers aimed at young audiences have included ''The Boy's Newspaper'' (1880\u20131882), ''[[The Children's Newspaper]]'' (1919\u20131965), and ''Early Times'' (launched in the late 1980s)</ref> Morgan was editorial director at ''First News'', responsible for bringing in celebrity involvement. He referred to the role as \"editorial overlord and frontman\".<ref name=\"firstnews\">{{Cite news |last=Burrell |first=Ian |title=Piers Morgan launches children's newspaper |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/piers-morgan-launches-childrens-newspaper-476277.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=1 May 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2006}}</ref>\n\nMorgan was filmed falling off a [[Segway PT|Segway]], breaking three ribs, in 2007. [[Simon Cowell]] outspokenly mocked Morgan's previous comment in 2003, in a ''[[Daily Mirror|Mirror]]'' headline after former U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] fell off a Segway:  \"You'd have to be an idiot to fall off wouldn't you, Mr&nbsp;President\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Andrew |last=Breitbart |url=http://www.breitbart.tv/reporter-who-called-bush-idiot-for-segway-fall-cracks-ribs-in-fall-from-contraption/ |title=Reporter Who Called Bush 'Idiot' for Segway Fall Cracks Ribs in Fall from Contraption |publisher=[[Breitbart TV]] |date=3 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912212119/http://www.breitbart.tv/reporter-who-called-bush-idiot-for-segway-fall-cracks-ribs-in-fall-from-contraption/ |archivedate=12 September 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url         = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a73424/morgan-had-broken-ribs-in-talent-final.html\n | title       = Morgan had broken ribs in 'Talent' final\n | publisher   = Digital Spy\n | date        = 23 August 2007\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | first       = Charles C. W.\n | last        = Cooke\n | title       = Piers Morgan, Feather Duster: CNN must be having second thoughts.\n | url         = http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/300536/piers-morgan-feather-duster-charles-c-w-cooke#\n | newspaper   = [[National Review]]\n | date        = 21 May 2012\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, following the revelation of [[Jimmy Savile]]'s [[Jimmy Savile sexual abuse scandal|sexual abuse against children]], Morgan said to have \"never met\" Savile in his lifetime; however, it was pointed out that in a 2009 piece by Morgan in ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]''{{'s}} ''Night & Day'' magazine he wrote that \"As I left, Jimmy Savile came up to me. 'Your TV shows are BRILLIANT!, he exclaimed. ... I've always loved Jimmy Savile.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Piers Morgan: did he meet Jimmy Savile or didn't he?|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/piers-morgan-did-he-meet-jimmy-savile-or-didnt-he-8222958.html|work=London Evening Standard|date=23 October 2012|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe became the editor-at-large of the ''[[Mail Online]]'' website's US operation in September 2014 and wrote several columns a week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Deans|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/sep/30/piers-morgan-joins-mail-online|title=Piers Morgan joins Mail Online as US editor-at-large|work=The Guardian|date=30 September 2014|accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Television career==\nMorgan's career expanded into television presenting before he left the ''Daily Mirror''. He presented a three-part television documentary series for the [[BBC]] titled ''The Importance of Being Famous'' (2003), about fame and the manner in which celebrities are covered by modern media. At the annual [[Pride of Britain Awards]] broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], Morgan chaired a panel of prominent people who had chosen the recipients of the awards from 1999 to 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prideofbritain.com/contentPages/judges/default.aspx |title=Judges |author=The Pride of Britain Awards |publisher=Trinity Mirror Group |accessdate=26 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140217203455/http://www.prideofbritain.com/contentPages/judges/default.aspx |archivedate=17 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHe co-hosted a current affairs interview show on [[Channel 4]] with [[Amanda Platell]], ''Morgan and Platell''. Morgan and Platell were put together because of their opposing political viewpoints; Platell interrogated guests from the right wing, Morgan from the left wing.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.newstatesman.com/200411080018 | title= Amanda Platell notes Piers Morgan's two left feet|newspaper=New Statesman |date=8 November 2004}}</ref> The show was dropped after three series reputedly because of poor viewing figures, although the chairman of Channel 4 [[Luke Johnson (Businessman)|Luke Johnson]] was reported not to like the programme.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/may/12/channel4.politicsandthemedia \"Morgan and Platell to return on Channel 4\"], ''The Guardian'', 12 May 2005</ref>\n\nThroughout 2006, Morgan appeared as a judge on the television show ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' alongside [[Brandy Norwood]] and [[David Hasselhoff]] on [[NBC]]. Morgan was chosen by Simon Cowell as a replacement for himself because of the conditions of his ''[[American Idol]]'' contract. Morgan appeared as a celebrity contestant on ''[[Comic Relief Does The Apprentice]]'' in 2007, to raise money for the BBC charity telethon [[Comic Relief (charity)|Comic Relief]]. After his team lost, Morgan was selected by [[Alan Sugar|Sir Alan Sugar]] as the contestant to be fired.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tvnews.virginmedia.com/news/?news_id=7543|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618102236/http://tvnews.virginmedia.com/news/?news_id=7543|archivedate=18 June 2008|title='Red Nose apprentice' Morgan fired|author=PA Entertainment|date= 16 March 2007|work=TV News|accessdate=8 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2007, Morgan appeared as a judge for the second season of ''America's Got Talent'' and also appeared as a judge on ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' on ITV, alongside [[Amanda Holden]] and Simon Cowell. He also presented ''You Can't Fire Me, I'm Famous'' on [[BBC One]]. He fronted a three-part documentary about [[Sandbanks]] for ITV entitled ''Piers Morgan on Sandbanks'' in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/Sandbanks/default.html|title=Sandbanks: Piers Morgan meets Dorset's mega-rich|date=10 January 2008|publisher=ITV|accessdate=8 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621170129/http://www.itv.com/Sandbanks/default.html|archivedate=21 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Morgan signed a two-year \"[[golden handcuffs]]\" deal with ITV in May, reportedly worth \u00a32&nbsp;million per year. As part of the deal, he would continue as a judge on ''Britain's Got Talent'' for at least two more series and front a new chat show. He also made some interview specials, plus three more documentaries from various countries. Morgan's golden handcuffs deal was the first signing by ITV's new director of television, [[Peter Fincham]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/may/29/itv.television|title=Piers Morgan: Britain's Got Talent judge signs two-year deal with ITV|last=Conlan|first=Tara|date= 29 May 2008|newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=8 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, he began a three-part series, ''[[Piers Morgan On...]]'', which saw him visit [[Dubai]], [[Monte Carlo]] and Hollywood.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Preston|first=John|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/4371911/Review-Piers-Morgan-in...-Dubai-ITV1-and-Jamie-Saves-Our-Bacon-Channel-4.html|title=Review: Piers Morgan in... Dubai (ITV) and Jamie Saves Our Bacon (Channel 4)|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=<!-- Friday. -->30 January 2009|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref> The programme returned for a second series in 2010 when Morgan visited [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] in one episode.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sutcliffe|first=Tom|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-weekends-television-wallander-sun-bbc1brpiers-morgan-on-las-vegas-sat-itv1brelvis-in-vegas-sun-bbc2-1856621.html|newspaper=The Independent |title =The Weekend's Television: Wallander, Sun, BBC1; Piers Morgan on Las Vegas, Sat, ITV; Elvis in Vegas, Sun, BBC2|date=4 January 2010|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2009, his began hosting ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]'' on ITV, with [[Sharon Osbourne]] as the subject of the first episode.<ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/4642466/Sharon-Osbourne-I-quit-X-Factor-because-of-Danni-Minogue.html|title=Sharon Osbourne: 'I quit X Factor because of Danni Minogue'|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=16 February 2009|first=Urmee|last=Khan}}</ref> Other guests on the programme included [[Cheryl Tweedy|Cheryl]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2010/oct/13/cheryl-cole-piers-morgan|title=Cheryl Cole to Piers Morgan: show me some love|newspaper=The Guardian|date=13 October 2010}}</ref> and the then Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article7047925.ece |title=Piers Morgan's Life Stories; Live FA Cup Football; A Kick in the Head: The Lure of Las Vegas; Casualty |newspaper=The Times|date=6 March 2010 |first1=David|last1=Chater |first2=Joe|last2=Clay}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2010, [[CNN]] announced that Morgan would replace [[Larry King]] in the network's evening line-up with his show, ''[[Piers Morgan Live]]'', beginning on 17 January 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|work=The Spy Report |publisher=Media Spy |date=9 September 2010 |accessdate=9 September 2010 |title=Piers Morgan signs on as Larry King replacement |url=http://www.mediaspy.org/report/2010/09/09/us-piers-morgan-signs-on-as-larry-king-replacement |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915063358/http://www.mediaspy.org/report/2010/09/09/us-piers-morgan-signs-on-as-larry-king-replacement/ |archivedate=15 September 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"signcnn2\">{{Cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 September 2010|accessdate=8 September 2010|title=Piers Morgan takes over in Larry King chatshow slot|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/08/piers-morgan-larry-king-chatshow|first=Jason|last=Deans}}</ref> After poor ratings, CNN announced that the show was to be axed.<ref>Charles Riley [http://money.cnn.com/2014/02/23/news/piers-morgan-cnn/index.html \"CNN to end 'Piers Morgan Live'\"], CNN, 24 February 2014</ref> It was cancelled in February 2014 and ended its run in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/piers-morgan-says-cnn-show-682688|title=Piers Morgan Says CNN Show Has Been Canceled|last=Hayden|first=Erik|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=23 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> Commenting on the viewing figures, Morgan said that he was \"a British guy debating American cultural issues, including guns, which has been very polarizing, and there is no doubt that there are many in the audience who are tired of me banging on about it.\"<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|last=Carr|first=David|title=Piers Morgan and CNN Plan End to His Prime-Time Show|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 February 2014|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/24/business/media/piers-morgan-and-cnn-plan-end-to-his-prime-time-show.html}}</ref>\n\nFrom 13 to 17 April 2015, Morgan guest-hosted five episodes of ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' on ITV and became a permanent co-host in November 2015, appearing alongside [[Susanna Reid]] and [[Charlotte Hawkins]].<ref>{{Cite news|work=The Guardian|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=14 October 2015|title=Piers Morgan handed permanent role on Good Morning Britain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/oct/13/piers-morgan-permanent-fixture-good-morning-britain}}</ref> \"You can't help but go into battle with him every morning\", Reid has said of her colleague with whom she has clashed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44524374|title=Susanna Reid in 'constant battle' with Piers Morgan|work=BBC News|date=19 June 2018|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2016 to 2017, Morgan interviewed female murderers on the TV series ''Killer Women with Piers Morgan''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Killer Women with Piers Morgan|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6172806/|others=Piers Morgan, Amanda Lewis, Sheila Davalloo|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2017/11/17/piers-morgan-calls-out-self-delusion-of-love-triangle-killer/|title=Piers Morgan calls out 'self-delusion' of love-triangle killer|date=18 November 2017|work=New York Post|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref> He also presented ''Serial Killer with Piers Morgan'', as part of the 2017 Crime & Punishment season on ITV. In October 2018, Morgan appeared as a cameo on ''[[Hollyoaks]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2018-10-18/hollyoaks-storm-week-to-feature-piers-morgan-and-carol-kirkwood-cameos/|title=Hollyoaks storm week to feature Piers Morgan and Carol Kirkwood cameos|work=Radio Times|date=18 October 2018|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\nMorgan was the winner of the U.S. celebrity version of ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 7)|The Apprentice]]'', in 2008. He was eventually the overall winner, being named Celebrity Apprentice by host [[Donald Trump]] on 27 March, ahead of fellow finalist, American country music star [[Trace Adkins]],<ref>Johnson, Caitlin (28 March 2008). [https://www.today.com/popculture/relative-unknown-wins-celebrity-apprentice-wbna23838097 \"Relative unknown wins \u2018Celebrity Apprentice\u2019\"]. [[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]''. [[NBC]].</ref><ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/03/28/piers-morgan-beats-trace-adkins-on-celebrity-apprentice-finale.html \"Piers Morgan Beats Trace Adkins on 'Celebrity Apprentice' Finale\"]. [[Associated Press]]/[[Fox News]]. 28 March 2008.</ref> and having raised substantially more cash than all the other contestants combined.<ref>Rocchio, Christopher (28 March 2008). [http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/piers-morgan-defeats-trace-adkins-wins-the-celebrity-apprentice-6804.php \"Piers Morgan defeats Trace Adkins, wins 'The Celebrity Apprentice'\"]. ''Reality TV World''.</ref> Morgan was called \"ruthless, arrogant, evil and obnoxious\" by Trump in the final.<ref name=\"Morgan2008\">{{cite news|last=Morgan|first=Piers|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/gq-entertainment-donald-trump-interview-piers-morgan|title=Donald Trump on sex, money and politics|work=[[GQ]]|orig-year=December 2008|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nMorgan stated he personally would not vote for Donald Trump in the [[2016 United States presidential election]] (though as a permanent resident of the United States, not a citizen, he is not qualified to vote).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/news/2016/03/02/piers-morgan-gives-qualified-endorsement-donald-trump|title=Piers Morgan gives qualified endorsement of Donald Trump|website=The Drum|access-date=25 February 2019}}</ref> He predicted Trump's election as President of the United States and has described himself as a close friend of Trump.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morgan|first1=Piers|title=It's weird when your friend becomes leader of the free world|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/2016/12/its-weird-when-your-friend-becomes-leader-of-the-free-world/|work=The Spectator|date=10 December 2016}}</ref> Morgan interviewed Donald Trump on ''Good Morning Britain'' in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Demianyk|first=Graeme|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/donald-trump-piers-morgan-good-morning-britain_uk_56f230f1e4b08af01be9c210|title=Donald Trump Tells Piers Morgan That Muslims Are 'Absolutely Not' Reporting Terrorists|work=HuffPost|date=23 March 2016|accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nMorgan appeared on ITV's ''[[Loose Women]]'' panel show in late January 2017, and was challenged to repudiate Donald Trump.<ref name=LooseWomen/> He refused to do so, despite stating that he disagreed with him on many issues relating to [[gun control]], [[Climate change in the United States|climate change]], abortion, and the [[Executive Order 13769|\"Muslim travel ban\"]], saying that he found the principle of the ban understandable, but disagreed with \"the way [Trump] has gone about it\".<ref name=LooseWomen>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/jan/30/piers-morgan-defends-friendship-with-donald-trump|title=Piers Morgan defends friendship with Donald Trump|work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=31 January 2017|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nNearly a fortnight later, on the American talk show ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'', Morgan said \"There is no [[Trump travel ban|Muslim ban]]\", as \"85% of the world's [[Muslims]] are allowed in the country\". Another participant in the discussion, Australian comedian [[Jim Jefferies (comedian)|Jim Jefferies]], immediately swore at Morgan and criticised his defence of Trump.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/jim-jefferies-piers-morgan-defence-of-donald-trump-muslim-ban-real-time-with-bill-maher-a7574746.html|title=Piers Morgan slammed by Jim Jefferies after defending Donald Trump on talk show ''Real Time with Bill Maher''|work=The Independent|date=11 February 2017|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> After the novelist [[J. K. Rowling]] tweeted \"Yes, watching Piers Morgan being told to fuck off on live TV is *exactly* as satisfying as I'd always imagined\", the two began an exchange of words on the social media site.<ref>{{cite news|last=Horton|first=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/02/11/never-read-harry-potter-jk-rowling-piers-morgan-twitter-row/|title='This is why I've never read Harry Potter': JK Rowling and Piers Morgan in Twitter row|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=11 February 2017|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Thorpe|first=Vanessa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/feb/11/jk-rowling-piers-morgan-trump-twitter-spat|title=Fantastic beefs and where to find them: JK Rowling at war with Piers Morgan|work=[[The Observer]] |location=London |date=11 February 2017|accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nMorgan criticised Trump after he retweeted [[Jayda Fransen]], deputy leader of the small right-wing party [[Britain First]] in late November 2017. He tweeted to Trump: \"What the hell are you doing retweeting a bunch of unverified videos by Britain First, a bunch of disgustingly [[Racism|racist]] [[Far-right politics|far-right]] extremists? Please STOP this madness & undo your retweets\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Welsh|first=Daniel|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/donald-trump-retweets-britain-first-piers-morgan_uk_5a1ebbd5e4b0dc52b02ad20a|title=Piers Morgan Condemns Donald Trump Over Britain First Retweets|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Morgan presented ''[[President Trump \u2013 The Piers Morgan Interview]]'' for ITV,<ref>{{cite news|first=Chloe |last=Farand|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/donald-trump-is-not-feminist-piers-morgan-interview-itv-a8181811.html |title=Donald Trump tells Piers Morgan: 'I wouldn't say I'm a feminist' |work=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-42850362/trump-i-would-have-taken-a-tougher-stand-in-getting-out |title=Trump: 'I would have taken a tougher stand in getting out' |work=BBC News|date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> which many thought of as \"sycophantic\" and a \"[[love-in]]\" for Trump.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Paul|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-01-29/piers-morgan-too-soft-on-donald-trump-in-sycophantic-itv-love-in-interview/|title=88% of viewers say Piers Morgan was too soft on Donald Trump in 'sycophantic' ITV 'love-in' interview|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=29 January 2018|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref> Of respondents to a ''[[Radio Times]]'' Twitter poll, 88% viewed Morgan as being not \"tough enough\" on Trump.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Morgan interviewed Trump again in July 2018 during his official visit to the UK, this time on [[Air Force One]] during an internal flight, in a TV special entitled ''Piers, The President and Air Force One''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2018-07-15/donald-trump-piers-morgan-itv-good-morning-britain/|title=Donald Trump tells ITV the Queen is 'an incredible woman' \u2013 and US and UK will make 'a great trade deal'|publisher=[[ITV News]]|date=15 July 2018|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Morgan wrote a letter to Trump formally applying to become [[White House Chief of Staff]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2018/12/11/piers-morgan-trump-chief-of-staff/|title=Celebrity Apprentice Winner Piers Morgan Asks to Be Trump's Chief of Staff|website=Fortune|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring Trump's [[state visit]] to the United Kingdom in [[List_of_presidential_trips_made_by_Donald_Trump_(2019)#June|June 2019]], Morgan once again interviewed Trump, this time at the [[Churchill War Rooms]].<ref>{{cite news |title=ITV to broadcast Piers Morgan's Donald Trump interview in prime-time slot |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2019-06-05/piers-morgan-donald-trump-gmb-interview-how-to-watch-itv-repeat/ |accessdate=9 June 2019 |work=Radio Times |date=5 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Ofcom complaints ==\n===Chinese mocking and racism accusations===\n\nDuring his career at ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'', Morgan has been the subject of thousands of complaints to the British watchdog, [[Ofcom]] relating to controversial comments. On 21 January 2020, Morgan was accused of racism and was hit by 1,095 Ofcom complaints<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heart.co.uk/showbiz/celebrities/piers-morgan-ofcom-complaints-chinese-mock/|title=Piers Morgan hit with 1095 Ofcom complaints after 'mocking Chinese language' on GMB|website=Heart|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/europe/article/3047137/racism-row-erupts-after-queen-elizabeths-oldest-grandson-peter|title=Royally milking it: race row after queen\u2019s grandson stars in Chinese ad|date=22 January 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> for his comments relating to a Chinese dairy advert, in which he said \"He's using ching chong ching milk\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/21/piers-morgan-horrifies-viewers-mocks-chinese-language-rant-peter-phillips-milk-ad-12092997/|title=Piers Morgan horrifies viewers as he mocks Chinese language on GMB|date=21 January 2020|website=Metro|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> Morgan also spoke over the advert, saying \"ching chang cho jo\". He was accused by online netizens as using language which is used to antagonise Chinese people and for mocking the Chinese language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/news/morgan-labelled-racist-over-impression/3926807/|title=Piers Morgan labelled \u2018racist\u2019 over impression|website=Morning Bulletin|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Penguin and gender neutrality comments===\n\nOn 11 September 2019, Morgan claimed he identified himself as \"a penguin\" in response to a news piece relating to gender neutrality, and said \"the world has gone nuts\" over gender. This attracted 950 [[Ofcom]] complaints from viewers. He was cleared of any wrongdoing in November 2019, and in response, Morgan admitted \"he was personally quite pleased\" with having one of the highest number of complaints to any British TV show in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/11/05/piers-morgan-feels-empowered-receiving-record-breaking-complaints-identifying-penguin-11042269/|title=Piers Morgan \u2018empowered\u2019 after complaints for identifying as a penguin|date=5 November 2019|website=Metro|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/piers-morgan-cleared-ofcom-over-20813491|title=Piers Morgan cleared by Ofcom over 950 complaints \u2013 but Susanna Reid in trouble|last=O'Sullivan|first=Kyle|date=5 November 2019|website=mirror|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\n\nOn 22 January 2018, during a story about a homeless [[Special Air Service|SAS]] veteran, who had a petition set up in his name calling on his local council to provide him with social housing, Morgan had refused to read out [[Herefordshire Council]]'s statement. This was judged by Ofcom to be unfair to the council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ofcom.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/121347/Issue-362-of-Ofcoms-Broadcast-and-On-Demand-Bulletin.pdf|title=OfCom|date=24 September 2018|website=Ofcom \u2013 complaint by Herefordshire County Council, Good Morning Britain|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2016, Ofcom received 70 complaints in relation to comments made by Morgan during interview with Christian magistrate Richard Page about gay marriage, that viewers felt \"implied Christians were homophobic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/style/celebrity/celebrity-news/ofcom-clears-piers-morgan-over-christianity-questions-on-good-morning-britain-34617691.html|title=Ofcom clears Piers Morgan over Christianity questions on Good Morning Britain|website=independent|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> Ofcom confirmed on 13 April 2016, that Morgan would not be investigated for his comments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/apr/11/piers-morgan-escapes-censure-over-christian-homophobe-remark|title=Piers Morgan escapes censure over Christian homophobe remark|date=11 April 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 February 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2015, Morgan was criticised by Ofcom for laughing as a guest repeatedly used the F-word live on air. Although Ofcom did not take action as his co-presenter [[Susanna Reid]] quickly apologised, the watchdog expressed concern at his behaviour.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/jun/15/piers-morgan-good-morning-britain-swearing|title=Piers Morgan criticised for laughing as Good Morning Britain guest swore on air|date=15 June 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 February 2020|last2=agencies|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Feuds==\n===Ian Hislop===\nMorgan appeared as a guest on the [[BBC]] satirical news quiz ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'' in an episode transmitted on 24 May 1996.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/have-i-got-news-for-you/felix-dexter-piers-morgan-clive-anderson/episode/143355/summary.html Have I Got News for You Episode Guide > Season 11, Episode 6] TV.com</ref> In it, show regular [[Ian Hislop]] accused Morgan of having him [[Stalking|followed]] and having his house watched. The conflict escalated and at one point the host, [[Angus Deayton]], asked if they wished to go outside and have a fight. Later on, guest panellist [[Clive Anderson]] confronted Morgan commenting, \"the last time I was rude to you, you sent photographers to my doorstep the next day\", to which Piers Morgan retorted, \"You won't see them this time.\" The audience responded loudly in favour of Hislop.<ref>''[[Have I Got News For You]]'' BBC2, Series 11 episode 6; Transmitted on 24 May 1996</ref> \"We're about to start exposing the moon-faced midget\", Morgan was quoted as saying in 2002, to which Hislop responded, \"all he's been offering for information about my private life is a \u00a350 reward. My friends think that's not nearly enough.\"<ref name=\"Summerskill\" />\n\nIn 2007, Hislop chose Morgan as one of his pet hates on ''[[Room 101 (British TV series)|Room 101]]''.<ref name=R101>''[[Room 101 (British TV series)|Room 101]]'' BBC2, Series 11 episode 6; Transmitted on 9 February 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/room_101/episodes/11/6/ Room 101 Episode 11.6 \u2013 Ian Hislop] British Comedy Guide</ref> In doing so, Hislop spoke of the history of animosity between himself and Morgan and said that after their exchange on ''Have I Got News For You'' (which was shown as a clip), Morgan's reporters were tasked with trying to get gossip on Hislop's private life (including phoning acquaintances of Hislop), and photographers were sent in case Hislop did anything untoward or embarrassing while in their presence. Neither the reporters nor the photographers succeeded. Hislop also said that Morgan had attempted to quell the feud in an article in ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'', saying, \"The war is over. I'm officially calling an end to hostilities, at least from my end. I'm sure it won't stop him carrying on his 'Piers Moron' stuff\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=Emily |date=4 April 2011 |title=Piers Morgan: The Biography |url=http://www.johnblakepublishing.co.uk/e-store/Piers-Morgan-The-Biography.html |location=London |publisher=[[John Blake (journalist)#John Blake Publishing|John Blake Publishing Ltd]] |page= |isbn=978-1843583516 |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> (''[[Private Eye]]'', the fortnightly satirical magazine which Hislop edits, regularly calls Morgan 'Piers Moron')<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=What a moron |newspaper=[[Private Eye]] |date=20 December 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hattenstone |first=Simon |date=12 October 2013 |title=Piers Morgan: 'I want to be at the centre of the big stuff' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/oct/12/piers-morgan-shooting-straight |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ellison |first=Sarah |author-link=Sarah Ellison |date=November 2012 |title=Blood, Sweat, and Piers |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2012/11/piers-morgan-criticized-hated-than-ignored |newspaper=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Hislop, who was working on a [[World War I]] documentary at the time, responded by asking \"Is that an armistice or an unconditional surrender?\" Although [[Paul Merton]] \u2013 host of ''Room 101'' at the time and good friend of Hislop \u2013 agreed to put Morgan into ''Room 101'', he then comically rejected Morgan as being \"too toxic\" for ''Room 101''.<ref name=R101/><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/feb/10/broadcasting.tvandradio1 \"Room 101, BBC1\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 February 2007</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Anthony |first=Andrew |author-link=Andrew Anthony |date=20 April 2010 |title=Piers Morgan: The man with stars in his eyes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2010/jun/20/profile-piers-morgan |newspaper=The Observer |accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nIn October 2003, journalist and television personality [[Jeremy Clarkson]] reportedly emptied a glass of water over Morgan during the last flight of [[Concorde]] for some photographs published in the ''Mirror''.<ref name=\"Media Monkey\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2004/mar/17/mediamonkey.pressandpublishing|author=Media Monkey|title=Clarkson and Morgan in tabloid tussle|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 March 2004|accessdate=8 June 2008}}</ref> In March 2004, at the [[British Press Awards]], Clarkson punched Morgan three times during another argument.<ref name=\"Media Monkey\"/>\n\nOn 4 February 2014, transgender advocate [[Janet Mock]] appeared as a guest on ''Piers Morgan Live'' to discuss her memoir, ''Redefining Realness''. After the interview aired, Mock sent a series of tweets criticising Morgan for describing Mock as being \"formerly a man\". Morgan responded that he had \"never been treated in such a disgraceful manner\" by a guest. On 5 February, Mock appeared as a guest again to debate the dispute.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hedgecock |first=Sarah |url=http://gawker.com/piers-morgan-demands-apology-from-disgraceful-trans-w-1516913568 |title=Piers Morgan Demands Apology from \"Disgraceful\" Trans Woman Guest |accessdate=6 February 2014 |newspaper=Gawker |date=5 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140206203218/http://gawker.com/piers-morgan-demands-apology-from-disgraceful-trans-w-1516913568 |archivedate= 6 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nMorgan strongly objected to the [[2017 Women's March|Women's March on Washington]] on 21 January 2017, the day after [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Trump's inauguration]], describing protesters as \"rabid feminists\" and the multiple protests as being \"vacuous\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oppenheim|first1=Maya|title=Piers Morgan just accused Ewan McGregor of being 'paedophile-loving hypocrite'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/piers-morgan-ewan-mcgregor-accuse-paedophile-loving-hypocrite-good-morning-britain-no-show-t2-a7543911.html|accessdate=27 February 2017|work=The Independent|date=24 January 2017}}</ref> The actor [[Ewan McGregor]] disagreed with Morgan's statements on the women's march and pulled out of appearing on ''Good Morning Britain'' the following Tuesday after discovering Morgan would be interviewing him, along with Reid.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-38729770|title=Ewan McGregor and Piers Morgan row over Good Morning Britain appearance|work=BBC News|date=24 January 2017|accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref> Morgan accused McGregor of being a \"paedophile-loving hypocrite\" for his past support of [[Roman Polanski]].<ref name=\"Aitkenhead\">{{cite news|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/jan/28/piers-morgan-im-just-putting-opinions-out-there-its-my-job|title=Piers Morgan: 'I'm just putting opinions out there. It's my job'|work=The Guardian|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Banned guests===\nIn May 2011, Morgan banned actor [[Hugh Grant]] from his shows on CNN and ITV after Grant spoke out against the need for the tabloid press. On Twitter he responded: \"Hugh Grant is now banned, in perpetuity, from @PiersTonight and Life Stories and anything else I ever do. Tedious little man.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/piers-morgan-bans-tedious-little-man-hugh-grant-from-cnn-show/|title=Piers Morgan bans 'tedious little man' Hugh Grant from CNN show|work=Press Gazette|date=18 May 2011|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2012, MTV referred to the bad relations between Piers Morgan and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], reporting that \"Morgan has apparently felt slighted over the years by Madonna...he claims he was lied to by the singer's publicist\".<ref name=\"Kaufman\">\"Madonna Banned...\" by Gil Kaufman, MTV, 28 March 2012; [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1681945/madonna-banned-piers-morgan.jhtml retrieved 30 September 2012]</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, it was reported that Morgan had also banned actor [[Kelsey Grammer]]. Morgan himself claimed, \"Kelsey Grammer saw a photo of [[Camille Grammer|his ex-wife Camille]] in the open of our show and legged it.\"<ref>\"Kelsey Grammer Walks Out on Piers Morgan\", ABC News, 20 September 2012; [http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/09/kelsey-grammer-walks-out-on-piers-morgan retrieved 30 September 2012]</ref> ''[[TVGuide]]'' reported, \"All plans were still a go for the segment until Grammer actually got in the hot seat and saw the footage the producers had planned to peg to the segment, including a picture of his ex-wife\".<ref>\"Kelsey Grammer storms off set\" by Emily Gagne, ''TVGuide.ca'', 20 September 2012; [http://tvguide.ca/TVNews/Articles/120920_grammer_leaves_piers_EG.htm retrieved 30 September 2012].</ref> On 26 September 2012, Fox 11 Los Angeles reported that \"many say [it] was an ambush by Piers\".<ref>Official Facebook page: ''FOX 11 Flash'', 26 September 2012; [https://www.facebook.com/FOX11Flash retrieved 30 September 2012]</ref> ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' reported that \"before the interview was scheduled, it was made clear that Grammer would answer all questions, including those about [his ex-wife]. His sole request was not to show any images of her.\"<ref>\"Kelsey Grammer, Piers Morgan: Actor Barred...\", ''HuffPost'', 27 September 2012; [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/27/kelsey-grammer-piers-morgan-cnn_n_1919662.html retrieved 30 September 2012]</ref>\n\n==Phone hacking allegations==\nDuring Morgan's tenure as editor, the ''Daily Mirror'' was advised by Steven Nott that voicemail interception was possible by means of a standard PIN code. Despite staff initially expressing enthusiasm for the story it did not appear in the paper, although it did subsequently feature in a ''[[South Wales Argus]]'' article and on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] in October 1999. On 18 July 2011 Nott was visited by officers of [[Operation Weeting]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/press/this-scandal-is-all-my-fault-says-salesman-2332669.html|first=Matt|last=Blake|title=This scandal is all my fault, says salesman|newspaper=The Independent|date=6 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe came under criticism for his \"boasting\" about phone hacking from [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Louise Mensch]], who has since apologised for these accusations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-14346050 |work=BBC News |title=MP Mensch apologises to Piers Morgan for hacking slur |date=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, in a sequence of articles, political blogger [[Paul Staines]] alleged that while editor of the ''Daily Mirror'' in 2002 Morgan published a story concerning the affair of [[Sven-Goran Eriksson]] and [[Ulrika Jonsson]] while knowing it to have been obtained by [[phone hacking]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Young |first=Toby |author-link=Toby Young |date=29 July 2011 |title=The net closes around Piers Morgan |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/tobyyoung/100098912/the-net-closes-around-piers-morgan/ |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2011, Morgan was a witness by satellite link from the United States at the [[Leveson Inquiry]].<ref name=\"BBCLeverson\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16259941 \"Piers Morgan tells Leveson: Daily Mirror did not hack phones\"], BBC News, 20 December 2011</ref> While he said he had no reason to believe that phone hacking had occurred at the ''Mirror'' while he was in charge there, he admitted to hearing a recording of an answerphone message left by [[Paul McCartney]] for [[Heather Mills]], but refused to \"discuss where that tape was played or who made [it] \u2013 it would compromise a source.\"<ref name=\"BBCLeverson\"/> Appearing as a witness at the same Inquiry on 9 February 2012, Mills was asked under oath if she had ever made a recording of Paul McCartney's phone call or had played it to Piers Morgan; she replied: \"Never\".<ref name=\"anon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/leveson-inquiry/9071901/Leveson-Inquiry-Heather-Mills-vows-she-did-not-play-Paul-McCartney-messages-to-Piers-Morgan.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|title=Leveson Inquiry: Heather Mills vows she did not play Paul McCartney messages to Piers Morgan|date=9 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Michael Holden\">{{cite web|author=Michael Holden|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/09/us-britain-hacking-morgan-idUSTRE8181CL20120209|agency=[[Reuters]]|title=Beatle's ex-wife says Piers Morgan heard hacked call|date=9 February 2012}}</ref> She said that she had never authorised Morgan, or anybody, to access or listen to her voicemails.<ref name=\"anon\"/> Mills told the inquiry that Morgan, \"a man that has written nothing but awful things about me for years\", would have relished telling the inquiry if she had played a personal voicemail message to him.<ref name=\"Michael Holden\"/>\n\nOn 23 May 2012, ''[[Newsnight]]'' presenter [[Jeremy Paxman]] was a witness at the Leveson Inquiry. He recalled a lunch with the ''Mirror'' editor in September 2002 at which Morgan outlined the means of hacking into a mobile phone.<ref>Dan Sabbagh and Lisa O'Carroll [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/may/23/leveson-piers-morgan-paxman \"Piers Morgan told me how to hack a phone, says Jeremy Paxman\"], ''The Guardian'', 23 May 2012.</ref>\n\nOn 28 November 2012, the [[Channel 4]] documentary ''Taking on the Tabloids'', fronted by actor and phone hacking victim [[Hugh Grant]], showed footage from a 2003 interview with Morgan by the singer and phone hacking victim [[Charlotte Church]], during which he explained to her how to avoid answerphone messages being listened to by journalists. He said: \"You can access ... voicemails by typing in a number. Now, are you really telling me that journalists aren\u2019t going to do that?\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Matilda Battersby|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/video-from-2003-shows-piers-morgan-talking-about-phone-hacking-8364468.html|title=Video from 2003 shows Piers Morgan talking about phone hacking|newspaper=The Independent|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tntmagazine.com/news/uk/video-new-clip-surfaces-showing-piers-morgan-talking-to-charlotte-church-about-phone-hacking|title=Video: New clip surfaces showing Piers Morgan talking to Charlotte Church about phone hacking|newspaper=[[TNT (magazine)|TNT]]|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 November 2012, the official findings of the [[Leveson Inquiry]] were released, in which [[Lord Justice Leveson]] said that Morgan's testimony under oath on phone hacking was \"utterly unpersuasive\". He stated:  \"[The] evidence does not establish that [Morgan] authorised the hacking of voicemails or that journalists employed by TMG [Trinity Mirror Group] were indulging in this practice ... What it does, however, clearly prove is that he was aware that it was taking place in the press as a whole and that he was sufficiently unembarrassed by what was criminal behaviour that he was prepared to joke about it.\"<ref name=\"Mark Sweney\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2012-11-28/key-moments-from-the-leveson-inquiry |title=Key moments from the Leveson Inquiry |publisher=ITV News |date=28 November 2012 |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 December 2013, Morgan was interviewed, under caution, by police officers from Operation Weeting investigating phone hacking allegations at ''[[Mirror Group Newspapers]]'' during his tenure as editor.<ref>Martin Evans [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/phone-hacking/10638562/Piers-Morgan-questioned-by-police-over-phone-hacking.html \"Piers Morgan questioned by police over phone-hacking\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'',.co.uk, 14 February 2014</ref>\n\nOn 24 September 2014, the [[Trinity Mirror]] publishing group admitted for the first time that some of its journalists had been involved in phone hacking and agreed to pay compensation to four people who sued for the alleged hacking of voicemails.<ref>Gallivan, Rory and Zekaria, Simon (September 2014) [https://online.wsj.com/articles/trinity-mirror-admits-liability-over-phone-hacking-1411547673 \u201cTrinity Mirror Admits Liability Over Phone Hacking\u201d], ''The Wall Street Journal'', 24 September 2014. Retrieved 29 September 2014</ref><ref>Sweney, Mark (September 2014). [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/sep/28/trinity-mirror-phone-hacking-claims-compensation \u201cTrinity Mirror faces up to the financial fallout as phone-hacking claims mount\u201d], ''The Guardian'', 28 September 2014. Retrieved 29 September 2014.</ref> Six other phone-hacking claims had already been settled. The BBC reported that it had seen legal papers showing that although the alleged hacking could have taken place as early as 1998, the bulk of the alleged wrongdoing took place in the early 2000s when Morgan was the ''Daily Mirror'' editor.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">BBC News online [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-29339756 \u201cPhone-hacking: Trinity Mirror admits liability\u201d], BBC News online, 24 September 2014 (Retrieved 29 September 2014)</ref> The admissions by Trinity Mirror came whilst the London Metropolitan Police investigation into the phone hacking allegations was ongoing. Morgan has always denied any involvement in the practice.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nMorgan married Marion Shalloe, a hospital ward sister,<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> in 1991. The couple had three sons, Albert, Spencer, and Stanley, and divorced in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burrell|first=Ian|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/piers-morgan-hack-of-the-day-1898171.html|title=Piers Morgan: Hack of the day|work=The Independent|date=13 February 2010|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2019032771334/piers-morgan-rare-photo-three-sons-loose-women/|title=Rare photo of Piers Morgan and his 3 handsome sons revealed on Loose Women|date=27 March 2019|website=HELLO!|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> In June 2010, he married his second wife, journalist [[Celia Walden]], daughter of the former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[George Walden]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/7853270/Piers-Morgan-marries-the-Telegraphs-Celia-Walden.html|title=Piers Morgan marries Celia Walden|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Morgan announced in mid 2011 that the couple were expecting a child,<ref>http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20500210,00.html</ref> and on 25 November 2011, Walden gave birth to a daughter, Elise, her first child and Morgan's fourth.<ref>http://www.celebritybabyscoop.com/2012/11/27/first-glimpse-of-piers-morgans-daughter-elise</ref>\n\nMorgan is a fan of [[Premier League]] football club [[Arsenal F.C.]]<ref name=\"Morgan comments\">{{cite news|title='Wenger fails again' \u2013 Piers Morgan scathing of Arsenal boss after David Ospina howler|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/champions-league/wenger-fails-again-piers-morgan-scathing-of-arsenal-boss-after-david-ospina-howler-31569375.html|work=Irish Independent|date=14 October 2015}}</ref> He was an outspoken critic of former Arsenal manager [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]] and called for his sacking on many occasions. Speaking in defence of Wenger in 2015, former Arsenal goalkeeper [[Bob Wilson (footballer, born 1941)|Bob Wilson]] labelled Morgan an \"incredibly pompous individual\".<ref name=\"Arsenal\">{{cite news|last=Menezes|first=Jack de|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/piers-morgan-hurt-after-arsenal-legend-bob-wilson-questions-his-support-for-the-gunners-and-labels-10073107.html|title=Piers Morgan 'hurt' after Arsenal legend Bob Wilson questions his support for the Gunners and labels him a 'pompous individual'|work=The Independent|date=26 February 2015|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> When Arsenal midfielder [[Aaron Ramsey]] met Morgan on 26 April 2015, Ramsey refused to shake his hand due to the criticism he received from Morgan during the 2012\u201313 season. Morgan has responded by calling Ramsey 'whatshisname'.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/aaron-ramsey-well-within-his-rights-to-refuse-handshake-with-arsenal-fan-piers-morgan-says-ian-10209316.html \"Aaron Ramsey 'well within his rights' to refuse handshake with Arsenal fan Piers Morgan, says Ian Wright\"]. Independent. Retrieved 14 October 2015</ref>\n\nPolitically, Morgan identified as a supporter of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in a 1994 interview.<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> In 2019 Morgan voted for the Kensington Conservative candidate in the 2019 UK General Election,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lbc.co.uk/politics/elections/general-election-2019/piers-morgan-reveals-how-he-voted-general-election/|title=Piers Morgan reveals how he voted in this year's General Election|website=LBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> after previously voting for the Animal Welfare Party. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/piers-morgan-declares-his-political-endorsement-ahead-of-the-general-election-10229934.html|title=Piers Morgan declares his political allegiance ahead of the vote and it's... unexpected|date=2015-05-07|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book| title=Secret Lives| year=1991| isbn=0-905846-95-8| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Blake|author2=John Sachs}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Private Lives of the Stars| year=1991| isbn=0-207-16941-1| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Angus and Robertson|author2=John Sachs}}\n* {{Cite book| title=To Dream a Dream: Amazing Life of Phillip Schofield| year=1992| isbn=1-85782-006-1| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Blake| url=https://archive.org/details/todreamdreamamaz00morg}}\n* {{Cite book| title=\"Take That\": Our Story| year=1993| isbn=1-85283-839-6| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Boxtree}}\n* {{Cite book| title=\"Take That\": On the Road| year=1994| isbn=1-85283-396-3| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Boxtree}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Va Va Voom!: A Year with Arsenal 2003\u201304| year=2004| isbn=0-413-77451-1| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Methuen}}\n* {{Cite book| title=The Insider: The Private Diaries of a Scandalous Decade| year=2005| isbn=0-09-190849-3 | last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Ebury Press| title-link=The Insider: The Private Diaries of a Scandalous Decade}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Don't You Know Who I am?| year=2007| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Ebury Press}}\n* {{Cite book| title=God Bless America: Misadventures of a Big Mouth Brit| year=2009| isbn=978-0-09-191393-9| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Ebury Press| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/godblessamericad0000morg}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Shooting Straight: Guns, Gays, God, and George Clooney| year=2013| isbn=978-1-4767-4505-3| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Gallery Books| url=https://archive.org/details/shootingstraight0000morg}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q557758|c=Category:Piers Morgan|n=Category:Piers Morgan|b=no|v=no|voy=no|wikt=no|s=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|q=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|604955}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3713857.stm Profile: Piers Morgan] BBC News, 14 May 2004\n* {{Cite episode |title=Desert Island Discs |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00krkct|series=Desert Island Discs | serieslink=Desert Island Discs |network=BBC |station=Radio 4 |airdate=7 June 2009}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = Main presenter of ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''\n| years = 2015\u2013present\n| before = [[Sean Fletcher]] and [[John Stapleton (English journalist)|John Stapleton]]\n| after = Incumbent\n}}{{succession box\n| title = Editor of the ''[[News of the World]]''\n| years = 1994\u20131995\n| before = [[Patsy Chapman]]\n| after = [[Phil Hall (journalist)|Phil Hall]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Editor of the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''\n| years = 1995\u20132004\n| before = [[Colin Myler]]\n| after = [[Richard Wallace (journalist)|Richard Wallace]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{The Sun editors}}\n{{Daily Mirror editors}}\n{{The Apprentice (American TV series)}}\n{{CNN Anchors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morgan, Piers}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Harlow College]]\n[[Category:English diarists]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:English social commentators]]\n[[Category:English television journalists]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) people]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail journalists]]\n[[Category:Daily Mirror people]]\n[[Category:Gun control advocates]]\n[[Category:News of the World people]]\n[[Category:Opinion journalists]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People educated at Priory School, Lewes]]\n[[Category:People from Lewes]]\n[[Category:People from Newick]]\n[[Category:The Sun (United Kingdom) people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Piers Morgan\n| image              = Piers Morgan at PaleyFest 2013.jpg\n| caption            = Morgan at PaleyFest 2013\n| birth_name         = Piers Stefan O'Meara\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1965|03|30}}\n| birth_place        = [[Newick]], East Sussex, England\n| television         = {{Flat list|\n* ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]''\n* ''[[America's Got Talent]]''\n* ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 7)|The Celebrity Apprentice]]''\n* ''[[The Dark Side of Fame with Piers Morgan]]''\n* ''[[Piers Morgan On...]]''\n* ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]''\n* ''[[Piers Morgan Live]]''\n* ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''\n}}\n| education          = [[Chailey School]]<br/>[[Priory School, Lewes]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Harlow College]]\n| nationality        = English \n| employer         = {{Flat list|\n* ''South London News'' (1985\u201388)\n* ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' (1989\u20131994)\n* ''[[News of the World]]'' (1994\u201395)\n* ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' (1995\u20132004)\n}}\n| occupation         = {{Flat list|\n* Television presenter\n* writer\n* [[Citizen journalism|journalist]]\n* columnist\n* [[Social criticism|social critic]]\n}}\n| years_active       = 1985\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Marion Shalloe|1991|2008|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Celia Walden]]<br>|24 June 2010}}\n| party              = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Piers Stefan Pughe-Morgan'''  ({{IPAc-en|p|\u026a\u0259r|s}}; [[Given name#Name at birth|n\u00e9]] '''O'Meara'''; born 30 March 1965) is an English broadcaster, journalist, writer, and television personality. He is currently a co-presenter of the [[ITV Breakfast]] programme ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' from Monday to Wednesday each week.\n\nMorgan began his career in [[Fleet Street]] as a writer and editor for several [[tabloid journalism|tabloid]] papers, including ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', ''[[News of the World]]'', and the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''. In 1994, aged 29, he was appointed editor of the ''News of the World'' by [[Rupert Murdoch]], which made him the youngest editor of a British national newspaper in more than half a century.<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> On television, he hosted ''[[Piers Morgan Live]]'' on [[CNN]] from 2011 to 2014, replacing ''[[Larry King Live]]'' in the timeslot following [[Larry King|King]]'s retirement.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100911024937/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/39060518/ns/today-entertainment \"Piers Morgan is Larry King's CNN replacement\"], MSNBC, 8 September 2010. Retrieved 7 February 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Piers Morgan's CNN show cancelled after 3 years|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/piers-morgan-s-cnn-show-cancelled-after-3-years-1.2548831|accessdate=24 February 2014|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=23 February 2014}}</ref> He was a judge on ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' and ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nudd|first=Tim|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20544255,00.html|title=Piers Morgan Leaving America's Got Talent|newspaper=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref> In 2008, Morgan won the seventh season of the US ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. Season 7)|Celebrity Apprentice]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Caitlin |date=28 March 2008 |title=Relative unknown wins 'Celebrity Apprentice' |url=http://www.today.com/id/23838097/ns/today-entertainment/t/relative-unknown-wins-celebrity-apprentice |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref> In the UK, he has presented ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]'' since 2009, and ''Good Morning Britain'' since 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|work=The Guardian|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=14 October 2015|title=Piers Morgan handed permanent role on Good Morning Britain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/oct/13/piers-morgan-permanent-fixture-good-morning-britain}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/08/01/piers-morgan-has-been-replaced-on-good-morning-britain/1/?tse_id=INF_6f69916076e411e785e8bfcdfe5d7856|title=Piers Morgan has been replaced on Good Morning Britain|work=PinkNews|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref> Morgan has written eight books, including four volumes of memoirs.\n\nWhile working at ''Daily Mirror'', he was in charge during the period that the paper was implicated in the [[News International phone hacking scandal|phone hacking scandal]]. In 2011, Morgan denied having ever hacked a phone or \"to my knowledge published any story obtained from the hacking of a phone\". In 2012, he was criticised in the findings of the [[Leveson Inquiry]] by chair [[Brian Leveson]] who stated that comments made in Morgan's testimony about phone hacking were \"utterly unpersuasive\" and \"that he was aware that it was taking place in the press as a whole and that he was sufficiently unembarrassed by what was criminal behaviour that he was prepared to joke about it\".<ref name=\"Mark Sweney\">{{cite news |last=Sweney |first=Mark |date=30 November 2012 |title=Piers Morgan claims over phone hacking branded 'utterly unpersuasive' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/nov/30/piers-morgan-phone-hacking-leveson-inquiry |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPiers Morgan was born in 1965 in [[Surrey]], England (although he moved to [[Newick]], Sussex, England after a few months<ref name=\"offaly\"/>) as Piers Stefan O'Meara, the son of Vincent Eamonn O'Meara, an Irish dentist originally from [[County Offaly]],<ref name=\"offaly\">[http://www.offalyindependent.ie/news/roundup/articles/2011/01/21/4002777-first-barack-now-piers-morgan-is-offaly-conquering Piers Morgan reference to his father's background], Offalyindependent.ie (cached), 21 January 2011. Retrieved 7 February 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/44111/pages/10035|title=Notices Under The Trustee Act, 1925|work=The London Gazette|date=13 September 1966|page=67}}</ref> and Gabrielle Georgina Sybille (n\u00e9e Oliver),<ref name=cantoph>{{cite web|url=http://website.lineone.net/~hstjw/p29.htm#i1071|first=Hugh|last=Wilding|title=Wildings & Thurleys, Cantophers & McConnells|year=2008}}</ref> who raised her son as a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref name=cantoph /> With regard to his religious views, Morgan still identifies as a Catholic due to his mother's influence, and believes in an [[afterlife]], but does not \"go to [[Sacrament of Penance|Confession]], probably because it would take me too long\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mance |first1=Henry |title=Piers Morgan on Trump, Twitter and the power of prayer |url=https://www.ft.com/content/eac296be-03fc-11e7-ace0-1ce02ef0def9 |accessdate=30 July 2018 |work=Financial Times |date=15 March 2017}}</ref> He has a brother, Jeremy, who is two years older.<ref name=\"Naughton\"/>\n\nHis father died when Morgan was 11 months old; his mother later married Glynne Pughe-Morgan,<ref>Piers Morgan, The Hot Seat: Love, War, and Cable News (2014), p. 5</ref><ref>Roy Greenslade, Press Gang: How Newspapers Make Profits from Propaganda (2004), p. 602</ref> a Welsh publican later in the meat distribution business, and he took his stepfather's surname.<ref name=\"Davies1994\">{{cite news |last=Davies |first=Hunter |author-link=Hunter Davies |date=13 December 1994 |title=From City boy to World leader |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/from-city-boy-to-world-leader-1387335.html |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> He was at the independent Cumnor House prep school <!-- boarded for two years. (Davies 1994) -->between the ages of seven and 13, then [[Chailey School]], a [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]] secondary school in [[Chailey]], near [[Lewes]], East Sussex. <!-- followed by [[Priory School, Lewes]], for the [[sixth form]]. --><ref name=\"Naughton\">{{Cite news|last1=Naughton|first1=Philippe|last2=Costello|first2=Miles|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/the-rhino-in-riot-gear-has-a-way-of-coaxing-out-secrets-3hvp7nw6kt2|title=The rhino in riot gear has a way of coaxing out secrets: PROFILE: Piers Morgan|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=6 April 2008|accessdate=16 July 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref> After nine months at [[Lloyd's of London]], Morgan studied journalism at [[Harlow College]].<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> Morgan joined the Surrey and South London Newspaper Group in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ortiz|first=Jen|title=SCANDALOUS! 11 Years in the Life of Piers Morgan|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/piers-morgan-hacking-murdoch-bio-2011-7|newspaper=Business Insider|accessdate=11 November 2011}}</ref> \n\n==Press career==\n===At the Murdoch titles===\nMorgan began to work as a freelance at ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' in 1988, at this point dropping his [[double-barrelled name]]. He told [[Hunter Davies]] in December 1994 that he was personally recruited by ''Sun'' editor [[Kelvin MacKenzie]] to work on the newspaper's show business column \"Bizarre\", his first high-profile post.<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> Although he was not a fan of pop music, he was considered skilled at self-publicity and became the column's main writer. \"I became the Friend of the Stars, a rampant egomaniac, pictured all the time with famous people \u2013 [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Sylvester Stallone|Stallone]], [[David Bowie|Bowie]], [[Paul McCartney]], hundreds of them. It was shameless, as they didn't know me from Adam\", he told Davies.<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/>\n\nMorgan left this post in 1995 shortly after publishing photographs of [[Victoria Aitken|Catherine Victoria Lockwood]], then wife of [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer|Charles, Earl Spencer]], leaving an addictive disorders clinic in Surrey.<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Rhys |date=12 May 1995 |title=Murdoch lashes editor shock |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/murdoch-lashes-editor-shock-1619121.html |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> This action ran against the editors' code of conduct,<ref name=\"BBC2004\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3713857.stm \"Profile: Piers Morgan\"], BBC News, 14 May 2004</ref> a misdemeanour for which the [[Press Complaints Commission]] upheld a complaint against Morgan.<ref name=\"BBC2004\"/> Murdoch was reported as having said that \"the boy went too far\"<ref>Ginny Dougary [http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/books/article2451447.ece \"Educating Piers\"], ''The Times Magazine'', 7 April 2007. {{subscription}}</ref> and publicly distanced himself from the story.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/47847.stm \"Earl Spencer loses privacy battle to Europe\"], BBC News, 16 January 1998</ref> Fearful of a privacy law action if he had not criticised one of his employees, Murdoch is said to have apologised to Morgan in private.<ref>Tom Watson and Martin Hickman [https://books.google.com/books?id=Lel9DjaPgqEC&pg=PT30 ''Dial M for Murdoch: News Corporation and the Corruption of Britain''], London: Penguin, 2012, p. 30</ref><ref>Benjamin Wallace [http://nymag.com/news/media/piers-morgan-2011-10/index1.html \"Piers Morgan Isn\u2019t Sleeping Well\"], ''New York'' (magazine), 9 October 2011</ref>\n\nThe incident was reported to have contributed to Morgan's decision to leave for the ''Daily Mirror'' editorship.<ref name=\"Summerskill\">{{cite news |last=Summerskill |first=Ben |author-link=Ben Summerskill |date=1 September 2002 |title=Has Piers now got news for Ian? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/sep/01/pressandpublishing.uknews |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Morgan's autobiography ''[[The Insider: The Private Diaries of a Scandalous Decade|The Insider]]'' states that he left the ''News of the World'' for the ''Mirror'' of his own choice. It asserts he was an admirer of former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] for most of her period of office, making the appointment surprising as the ''Mirror'' is a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]-supporting title.<ref name=\"Naughton\"/>\n\n===''Daily Mirror'' editor===\nAs editor of the ''Daily Mirror'', Morgan was forced to apologise on television for the headline (rendered in upper case) \"Achtung Surrender! For You Fritz Ze Euro Championship Is Over\" on 25 June 1996, a day before [[England national football team|England]] met [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in a semi-final of the [[1996 European Football Championship|Euro '96]] football championships.<ref>{{cite news |last=Maguire |first=Kevin |author-link=Kevin Maguire (journalist) |date=25 February 2002 |title=The New Statesman Profile \u2013 Piers Morgan |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/node/142285 |newspaper=[[New Statesman]] |location=London |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Byrne |first=Ciar |date=15 May 2004 |title=Piers Morgan: The man with no moral compass who found his destiny in a steadfast opposition to war |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/piers-morgan-the-man-with-no-moral-compass-who-found-his-destiny-in-a-steadfast-opposition-to-war-6169902.html |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref><ref>George Wilkes and Dominic Wing \"The British Press and European Integration: 1948 to 1996\", in David Baker, David Seawright (eds.) [https://books.google.com/books?id=MBKbtzPdbhQC&pg=PA202 ''Britain for and Against Europe: British Politics and the Question of European Integration''], Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1998, p. 202</ref><ref name=\"IHT\">{{Cite news |last=Thomsen |first=Ian |date=26 June 1996 |title=Oh, Sorry: Tabloids Lose the Soccer War |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/06/26/news/26iht-england.t_0.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=3 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nA\u00a316&nbsp;million package of investment in the title was rolled out from January, including the dropping of \"''Daily''\" from the masthead in February,<ref>Roy Greenslade ''Press Gang: How Newspapers Make Profits From Propaganda'', London: Pan, 2004 [2003], p. 657</ref> which was later reversed. [[Roy Greenslade]] wrote in August 1999 that Morgan's editorship \"has made a huge difference: his enormous enthusiasm, determination and focus is a major plus\".<ref>Roy Greenslade [https://www.theguardian.com/media/1999/aug/16/mondaymediasection.columnists \"Chasing the Sun's tail\"], ''The Guardian'', 16 August 1999</ref>\n\nMorgan was the subject of an investigation in 2000 after Suzy Jagger wrote an article for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' revealing that he had bought [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]20,000 worth of shares in the computer company [[Viglen]] soon before the ''Mirror'' 's \"City Slickers\" column tipped Viglen as a good buy.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jagger |first=Suzy |title=Mirror editor saw his shares soar after paper tipped company |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/2000/02/02/nmir02.html |url-status=dead |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021122223139/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=%2Farchive%2F2000%2F02%2F02%2Fnmir02.html |archivedate=22 November 2002 |accessdate=13 January 2015 }}</ref> Morgan was found by the [[Press Complaints Commission]] to have breached the Code of Conduct on financial journalism, but kept his job. The \"City Slickers\" columnists, [[Anil Bhoyrul]] and [[James Hipwell]], were both found to have committed further breaches of the Code and were sacked before the inquiry concluded.<ref>{{cite news |last=Moyes |first=Jojo |author-link=Jojo Moyes |date=10 May 2000 |title=Columnist rewrites his 'Mirror' tips story over share tips |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/columnist-rewrites-his-mirror-tips-story-over-share-tips-279320.html |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Further enquiry by the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] in 2004 cleared Morgan of any charges.<ref name=\"cleared\">{{Cite news |title=Morgan cleared after shares probe |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3792225.stm |work=BBC News |date=10 June 2004}}</ref> On 7 December 2005, Bhoyrul and Hipwell were convicted of conspiracy to breach the Financial Services Act. During the trial it emerged that Morgan had bought \u00a367,000 worth of Viglen shares, emptying his bank account and investing under his (first) wife's name, too.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tryhorn |first=Chris  |date=23 November 2005 |title=Mirror editor 'bought \u00a367,000 of shares before they were tipped' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/nov/23/business.pressandpublishing |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Mirror'' attempted to move mid-market in 2002, eschewing the more trivial stories of show-business and gossip, but sales declined.<ref name=\"Naughton\"/><ref name=\"Barber\">{{cite news|last=Barber|first=Lynn|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/nov/20/newspaperformats.mirror|title=I should have been fired years ago, to be honest|work=The Observer|date=20 November 2005|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> In the wake of the [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse|Abu Ghraib torture scandal]], Morgan was sacked as editor of the ''Daily Mirror'' \"with immediate effect\" on 14 May 2004, after refusing to apologise to [[Sly Bailey]], then head of [[Trinity Mirror]], for authorising the newspaper's publication of photographs which had been shown to be false.<ref>Chris Tryhorn and Lisa O'Carroll [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2004/may/14/pressandpublishing.iraqandthemedia \"Morgan sacked from Daily Mirror\"], ''Media Guardian'', 14 May 2004</ref> These were alleged to show Iraqi prisoners being abused by [[British Army]] soldiers from the [[Queen's Lancashire Regiment]].<ref>{{Cite news\n |title=Daily Mirror statement in full \n |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html \n |publisher=CNN \n |date=13 May 2004 \n |accessdate=22 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041125053916/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/13/iraq.abuse.statement/index.html \n |archivedate=25 November 2004 |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> When, within days the photographs were shown to be crude fakes, under the headline \"SORRY..WE WERE HOAXED\", the ''Mirror'' responded that it had fallen victim to a \"calculated and malicious hoax\" and apologised for the publication of the photographs.<ref>{{Cite news\n | title       = Editor sacked over 'hoax' photos\n | url         = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/3716151.stm\n | publisher   = BBC News\n | date        = 14 May 2004\n | accessdate  = 27 December 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n | url         = http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/\n | title       = Fake abuse photos: Editor quits\n | publisher   = CNN\n | date        = 15 May 2004\n | archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20041012123314/http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/14/iraq.abuse.uk/\n | archivedate=12 October 2004}}</ref> However, Morgan has refused to admit that the photographs were faked, and has stated that the abuse shown in the photographs is similar to the sort of abuse which was happening in the British Army in Iraq at the time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Byers|first1=Dylan|title=Piers Morgan on phone-hacking, Iraq photos|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/01/piers-morgan-on-phone-hacking-iraq-photos-154551|accessdate=30 January 2018|work=Politico|date=18 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Post-''Mirror'' press career===\nIn partnership with [[Matthew Freud]], he gained ownership in May 2005 of ''[[Press Gazette]]'', a media trade publication together with its \"[[cash cow]]\", the [[British Press Awards]], in a deal worth \u00a31&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"pgdeal\">{{Cite news\n |first       = Jemima\n |last        = Kiss\n |title       = Piers Morgan clinches Press Gazette deal\n |url         = http://www.journalism.co.uk/2/articles/51408.php\n |publisher   = [[Journalism.co.uk]]\n |date        = 13 June 2005\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20091003002526/http://www.journalism.co.uk/2/articles/51408.php\n |archivedate = 3 October 2009\n|df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=\"prop\">{{Cite news\n | first       = Julia\n | last        = Day\n | title       = Piers Morgan turns proprietor with purchase of Press Gazette\n | url         = https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/may/28/pressandpublishing.uknews\n | newspaper   = The Guardian\n | date        = 28 May 2005\n | accessdate  = 22 May 2010\n}}</ref> This ownership was cited as one of the reasons many major newspapers boycotted the [[British Press Awards 2006#Controversy leading up to the 2006 awards|2006 awards]].<ref name=\"boyc\">{{Cite news\n | first       = Roy\n | last        = Greenslade\n | author-link = Roy Greenslade\n | title       = Big titles boycott Morgans organ press awards\n | url         = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2930708/Big-titles-boycott-Morgans-organ-press-awards.html\n | work   = The Daily Telegraph\n | date        = 24 January 2006\n | accessdate  = 22 May 2010\n}}</ref> ''Press Gazette'' entered [[administrative receivership]] toward the end of 2006,<ref>{{Cite news\n | first       = Roy\n | last        = Greenslade\n | title       = Press Gazette now in administration\n | url         = https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2006/nov/06/pressgazettenowinadministr\n | work   = The Guardian\n | date        = 6 November 2006\n | accessdate  = 27 December 2012\n}}</ref> before being sold to a trade buyer.\n\n''[[First News (newspaper)|First News]]'' was launched by Morgan on 4 May 2006. A weekly paper aimed at seven to 14-year-olds, he said at its launch that the paper was to be \"Britain's first national newspaper for children\".<ref>\"Britain's first national newspaper for children to launch Friday\", Associated Press, 4 May 2006</ref><ref>Other newspapers aimed at young audiences have included ''The Boy's Newspaper'' (1880\u20131882), ''[[The Children's Newspaper]]'' (1919\u20131965), and ''Early Times'' (launched in the late 1980s)</ref> Morgan was editorial director at ''First News'', responsible for bringing in celebrity involvement. He referred to the role as \"editorial overlord and frontman\".<ref name=\"firstnews\">{{Cite news |last=Burrell |first=Ian |title=Piers Morgan launches children's newspaper |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/piers-morgan-launches-childrens-newspaper-476277.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=1 May 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2006}}</ref>\n\nMorgan was filmed falling off a [[Segway PT|Segway]], breaking three ribs, in 2007. [[Simon Cowell]] outspokenly mocked Morgan's previous comment in 2003, in a ''[[Daily Mirror|Mirror]]'' headline after former U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] fell off a Segway:  \"You'd have to be an idiot to fall off wouldn't you, Mr&nbsp;President\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Andrew |last=Breitbart |url=http://www.breitbart.tv/reporter-who-called-bush-idiot-for-segway-fall-cracks-ribs-in-fall-from-contraption/ |title=Reporter Who Called Bush 'Idiot' for Segway Fall Cracks Ribs in Fall from Contraption |publisher=[[Breitbart TV]] |date=3 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912212119/http://www.breitbart.tv/reporter-who-called-bush-idiot-for-segway-fall-cracks-ribs-in-fall-from-contraption/ |archivedate=12 September 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url         = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a73424/morgan-had-broken-ribs-in-talent-final.html\n | title       = Morgan had broken ribs in 'Talent' final\n | publisher   = Digital Spy\n | date        = 23 August 2007\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | first       = Charles C. W.\n | last        = Cooke\n | title       = Piers Morgan, Feather Duster: CNN must be having second thoughts.\n | url         = http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/300536/piers-morgan-feather-duster-charles-c-w-cooke#\n | newspaper   = [[National Review]]\n | date        = 21 May 2012\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, following the revelation of [[Jimmy Savile]]'s [[Jimmy Savile sexual abuse scandal|sexual abuse against children]], Morgan said to have \"never met\" Savile in his lifetime; however, it was pointed out that in a 2009 piece by Morgan in ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]''{{'s}} ''Night & Day'' magazine he wrote that \"As I left, Jimmy Savile came up to me. 'Your TV shows are BRILLIANT!, he exclaimed. ... I've always loved Jimmy Savile.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Piers Morgan: did he meet Jimmy Savile or didn't he?|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/piers-morgan-did-he-meet-jimmy-savile-or-didnt-he-8222958.html|work=London Evening Standard|date=23 October 2012|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe became the editor-at-large of the ''[[Mail Online]]'' website's US operation in September 2014 and wrote several columns a week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Deans|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/sep/30/piers-morgan-joins-mail-online|title=Piers Morgan joins Mail Online as US editor-at-large|work=The Guardian|date=30 September 2014|accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Television career==\nMorgan's career expanded into television presenting before he left the ''Daily Mirror''. He presented a three-part television documentary series for the [[BBC]] titled ''The Importance of Being Famous'' (2003), about fame and the manner in which celebrities are covered by modern media. At the annual [[Pride of Britain Awards]] broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], Morgan chaired a panel of prominent people who had chosen the recipients of the awards from 1999 to 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prideofbritain.com/contentPages/judges/default.aspx |title=Judges |author=The Pride of Britain Awards |publisher=Trinity Mirror Group |accessdate=26 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140217203455/http://www.prideofbritain.com/contentPages/judges/default.aspx |archivedate=17 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHe co-hosted a current affairs interview show on [[Channel 4]] with [[Amanda Platell]], ''Morgan and Platell''. Morgan and Platell were put together because of their opposing political viewpoints; Platell interrogated guests from the right wing, Morgan from the left wing.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.newstatesman.com/200411080018 | title= Amanda Platell notes Piers Morgan's two left feet|newspaper=New Statesman |date=8 November 2004}}</ref> The show was dropped after three series reputedly because of poor viewing figures, although the chairman of Channel 4 [[Luke Johnson (Businessman)|Luke Johnson]] was reported not to like the programme.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/may/12/channel4.politicsandthemedia \"Morgan and Platell to return on Channel 4\"], ''The Guardian'', 12 May 2005</ref>\n\nThroughout 2006, Morgan appeared as a judge on the television show ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' alongside [[Brandy Norwood]] and [[David Hasselhoff]] on [[NBC]]. Morgan was chosen by Simon Cowell as a replacement for himself because of the conditions of his ''[[American Idol]]'' contract. Morgan appeared as a celebrity contestant on ''[[Comic Relief Does The Apprentice]]'' in 2007, to raise money for the BBC charity telethon [[Comic Relief (charity)|Comic Relief]]. After his team lost, Morgan was selected by [[Alan Sugar|Sir Alan Sugar]] as the contestant to be fired.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tvnews.virginmedia.com/news/?news_id=7543|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618102236/http://tvnews.virginmedia.com/news/?news_id=7543|archivedate=18 June 2008|title='Red Nose apprentice' Morgan fired|author=PA Entertainment|date= 16 March 2007|work=TV News|accessdate=8 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2007, Morgan appeared as a judge for the second season of ''America's Got Talent'' and also appeared as a judge on ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' on ITV, alongside [[Amanda Holden]] and Simon Cowell. He also presented ''You Can't Fire Me, I'm Famous'' on [[BBC One]]. He fronted a three-part documentary about [[Sandbanks]] for ITV entitled ''Piers Morgan on Sandbanks'' in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/Sandbanks/default.html|title=Sandbanks: Piers Morgan meets Dorset's mega-rich|date=10 January 2008|publisher=ITV|accessdate=8 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621170129/http://www.itv.com/Sandbanks/default.html|archivedate=21 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Morgan signed a two-year \"[[golden handcuffs]]\" deal with ITV in May, reportedly worth \u00a32&nbsp;million per year. As part of the deal, he would continue as a judge on ''Britain's Got Talent'' for at least two more series and front a new chat show. He also made some interview specials, plus three more documentaries from various countries. Morgan's golden handcuffs deal was the first signing by ITV's new director of television, [[Peter Fincham]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/may/29/itv.television|title=Piers Morgan: Britain's Got Talent judge signs two-year deal with ITV|last=Conlan|first=Tara|date= 29 May 2008|newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=8 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2009, he began a three-part series, ''[[Piers Morgan On...]]'', which saw him visit [[Dubai]], [[Monte Carlo]] and Hollywood.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Preston|first=John|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/4371911/Review-Piers-Morgan-in...-Dubai-ITV1-and-Jamie-Saves-Our-Bacon-Channel-4.html|title=Review: Piers Morgan in... Dubai (ITV) and Jamie Saves Our Bacon (Channel 4)|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=<!-- Friday. -->30 January 2009|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref> The programme returned for a second series in 2010 when Morgan visited [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] in one episode.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sutcliffe|first=Tom|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-weekends-television-wallander-sun-bbc1brpiers-morgan-on-las-vegas-sat-itv1brelvis-in-vegas-sun-bbc2-1856621.html|newspaper=The Independent |title =The Weekend's Television: Wallander, Sun, BBC1; Piers Morgan on Las Vegas, Sat, ITV; Elvis in Vegas, Sun, BBC2|date=4 January 2010|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2009, his began hosting ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]'' on ITV, with [[Sharon Osbourne]] as the subject of the first episode.<ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/4642466/Sharon-Osbourne-I-quit-X-Factor-because-of-Danni-Minogue.html|title=Sharon Osbourne: 'I quit X Factor because of Danni Minogue'|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=16 February 2009|first=Urmee|last=Khan}}</ref> Other guests on the programme included [[Cheryl Tweedy|Cheryl]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2010/oct/13/cheryl-cole-piers-morgan|title=Cheryl Cole to Piers Morgan: show me some love|newspaper=The Guardian|date=13 October 2010}}</ref> and the then Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article7047925.ece |title=Piers Morgan's Life Stories; Live FA Cup Football; A Kick in the Head: The Lure of Las Vegas; Casualty |newspaper=The Times|date=6 March 2010 |first1=David|last1=Chater |first2=Joe|last2=Clay}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2010, [[CNN]] announced that Morgan would replace [[Larry King]] in the network's evening line-up with his show, ''[[Piers Morgan Live]]'', beginning on 17 January 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|work=The Spy Report |publisher=Media Spy |date=9 September 2010 |accessdate=9 September 2010 |title=Piers Morgan signs on as Larry King replacement |url=http://www.mediaspy.org/report/2010/09/09/us-piers-morgan-signs-on-as-larry-king-replacement |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915063358/http://www.mediaspy.org/report/2010/09/09/us-piers-morgan-signs-on-as-larry-king-replacement/ |archivedate=15 September 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"signcnn2\">{{Cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 September 2010|accessdate=8 September 2010|title=Piers Morgan takes over in Larry King chatshow slot|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/08/piers-morgan-larry-king-chatshow|first=Jason|last=Deans}}</ref> After poor ratings, CNN announced that the show was to be axed.<ref>Charles Riley [http://money.cnn.com/2014/02/23/news/piers-morgan-cnn/index.html \"CNN to end 'Piers Morgan Live'\"], CNN, 24 February 2014</ref> It was cancelled in February 2014 and ended its run in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/piers-morgan-says-cnn-show-682688|title=Piers Morgan Says CNN Show Has Been Canceled|last=Hayden|first=Erik|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=23 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> Commenting on the viewing figures, Morgan said that he was \"a British guy debating American cultural issues, including guns, which has been very polarizing, and there is no doubt that there are many in the audience who are tired of me banging on about it.\"<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|last=Carr|first=David|title=Piers Morgan and CNN Plan End to His Prime-Time Show|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 February 2014|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/24/business/media/piers-morgan-and-cnn-plan-end-to-his-prime-time-show.html}}</ref>\n\nFrom 13 to 17 April 2015, Morgan guest-hosted five episodes of ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' on ITV and became a permanent co-host in November 2015, appearing alongside [[Susanna Reid]] and [[Charlotte Hawkins]].<ref>{{Cite news|work=The Guardian|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=14 October 2015|title=Piers Morgan handed permanent role on Good Morning Britain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/oct/13/piers-morgan-permanent-fixture-good-morning-britain}}</ref> \"You can't help but go into battle with him every morning\", Reid has said of her colleague with whom she has clashed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44524374|title=Susanna Reid in 'constant battle' with Piers Morgan|work=BBC News|date=19 June 2018|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2016 to 2017, Morgan interviewed female murderers on the TV series ''Killer Women with Piers Morgan''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Killer Women with Piers Morgan|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6172806/|others=Piers Morgan, Amanda Lewis, Sheila Davalloo|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2017/11/17/piers-morgan-calls-out-self-delusion-of-love-triangle-killer/|title=Piers Morgan calls out 'self-delusion' of love-triangle killer|date=18 November 2017|work=New York Post|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref> He also presented ''Serial Killer with Piers Morgan'', as part of the 2017 Crime & Punishment season on ITV. In October 2018, Morgan appeared as a cameo on ''[[Hollyoaks]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2018-10-18/hollyoaks-storm-week-to-feature-piers-morgan-and-carol-kirkwood-cameos/|title=Hollyoaks storm week to feature Piers Morgan and Carol Kirkwood cameos|work=Radio Times|date=18 October 2018|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\nMorgan was the winner of the U.S. celebrity version of ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 7)|The Apprentice]]'', in 2008. He was eventually the overall winner, being named Celebrity Apprentice by host [[Donald Trump]] on 27 March, ahead of fellow finalist, American country music star [[Trace Adkins]],<ref>Johnson, Caitlin (28 March 2008). [https://www.today.com/popculture/relative-unknown-wins-celebrity-apprentice-wbna23838097 \"Relative unknown wins \u2018Celebrity Apprentice\u2019\"]. [[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]''. [[NBC]].</ref><ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/03/28/piers-morgan-beats-trace-adkins-on-celebrity-apprentice-finale.html \"Piers Morgan Beats Trace Adkins on 'Celebrity Apprentice' Finale\"]. [[Associated Press]]/[[Fox News]]. 28 March 2008.</ref> and having raised substantially more cash than all the other contestants combined.<ref>Rocchio, Christopher (28 March 2008). [http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/piers-morgan-defeats-trace-adkins-wins-the-celebrity-apprentice-6804.php \"Piers Morgan defeats Trace Adkins, wins 'The Celebrity Apprentice'\"]. ''Reality TV World''.</ref> Morgan was called \"ruthless, arrogant, evil and obnoxious\" by Trump in the final.<ref name=\"Morgan2008\">{{cite news|last=Morgan|first=Piers|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/gq-entertainment-donald-trump-interview-piers-morgan|title=Donald Trump on sex, money and politics|work=[[GQ]]|orig-year=December 2008|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nMorgan stated he personally would not vote for Donald Trump in the [[2016 United States presidential election]] (though as a permanent resident of the United States, not a citizen, he is not qualified to vote).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/news/2016/03/02/piers-morgan-gives-qualified-endorsement-donald-trump|title=Piers Morgan gives qualified endorsement of Donald Trump|website=The Drum|access-date=25 February 2019}}</ref> He predicted Trump's election as President of the United States and has described himself as a close friend of Trump.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morgan|first1=Piers|title=It's weird when your friend becomes leader of the free world|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/2016/12/its-weird-when-your-friend-becomes-leader-of-the-free-world/|work=The Spectator|date=10 December 2016}}</ref> Morgan interviewed Donald Trump on ''Good Morning Britain'' in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Demianyk|first=Graeme|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/donald-trump-piers-morgan-good-morning-britain_uk_56f230f1e4b08af01be9c210|title=Donald Trump Tells Piers Morgan That Muslims Are 'Absolutely Not' Reporting Terrorists|work=HuffPost|date=23 March 2016|accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nMorgan appeared on ITV's ''[[Loose Women]]'' panel show in late January 2017, and was challenged to repudiate Donald Trump.<ref name=LooseWomen/> He refused to do so, despite stating that he disagreed with him on many issues relating to [[gun control]], [[Climate change in the United States|climate change]], abortion, and the [[Executive Order 13769|\"Muslim travel ban\"]], saying that he found the principle of the ban understandable, but disagreed with \"the way [Trump] has gone about it\".<ref name=LooseWomen>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/jan/30/piers-morgan-defends-friendship-with-donald-trump|title=Piers Morgan defends friendship with Donald Trump|work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |date=31 January 2017|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nNearly a fortnight later, on the American talk show ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'', Morgan said \"There is no [[Trump travel ban|Muslim ban]]\", as \"85% of the world's [[Muslims]] are allowed in the country\". Another participant in the discussion, Australian comedian [[Jim Jefferies (comedian)|Jim Jefferies]], immediately swore at Morgan and criticised his defence of Trump.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/jim-jefferies-piers-morgan-defence-of-donald-trump-muslim-ban-real-time-with-bill-maher-a7574746.html|title=Piers Morgan slammed by Jim Jefferies after defending Donald Trump on talk show ''Real Time with Bill Maher''|work=The Independent|date=11 February 2017|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> After the novelist [[J. K. Rowling]] tweeted \"Yes, watching Piers Morgan being told to fuck off on live TV is *exactly* as satisfying as I'd always imagined\", the two began an exchange of words on the social media site.<ref>{{cite news|last=Horton|first=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/02/11/never-read-harry-potter-jk-rowling-piers-morgan-twitter-row/|title='This is why I've never read Harry Potter': JK Rowling and Piers Morgan in Twitter row|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=11 February 2017|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Thorpe|first=Vanessa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/feb/11/jk-rowling-piers-morgan-trump-twitter-spat|title=Fantastic beefs and where to find them: JK Rowling at war with Piers Morgan|work=[[The Observer]] |location=London |date=11 February 2017|accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nMorgan criticised Trump after he retweeted [[Jayda Fransen]], deputy leader of the small right-wing party [[Britain First]] in late November 2017. He tweeted to Trump: \"What the hell are you doing retweeting a bunch of unverified videos by Britain First, a bunch of disgustingly [[Racism|racist]] [[Far-right politics|far-right]] extremists? Please STOP this madness & undo your retweets\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Welsh|first=Daniel|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/donald-trump-retweets-britain-first-piers-morgan_uk_5a1ebbd5e4b0dc52b02ad20a|title=Piers Morgan Condemns Donald Trump Over Britain First Retweets|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Morgan presented ''[[President Trump \u2013 The Piers Morgan Interview]]'' for ITV,<ref>{{cite news|first=Chloe |last=Farand|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/donald-trump-is-not-feminist-piers-morgan-interview-itv-a8181811.html |title=Donald Trump tells Piers Morgan: 'I wouldn't say I'm a feminist' |work=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-42850362/trump-i-would-have-taken-a-tougher-stand-in-getting-out |title=Trump: 'I would have taken a tougher stand in getting out' |work=BBC News|date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> which many thought of as \"sycophantic\" and a \"[[love-in]]\" for Trump.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Paul|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-01-29/piers-morgan-too-soft-on-donald-trump-in-sycophantic-itv-love-in-interview/|title=88% of viewers say Piers Morgan was too soft on Donald Trump in 'sycophantic' ITV 'love-in' interview|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=29 January 2018|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref> Of respondents to a ''[[Radio Times]]'' Twitter poll, 88% viewed Morgan as being not \"tough enough\" on Trump.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Morgan interviewed Trump again in July 2018 during his official visit to the UK, this time on [[Air Force One]] during an internal flight, in a TV special entitled ''Piers, The President and Air Force One''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2018-07-15/donald-trump-piers-morgan-itv-good-morning-britain/|title=Donald Trump tells ITV the Queen is 'an incredible woman' \u2013 and US and UK will make 'a great trade deal'|publisher=[[ITV News]]|date=15 July 2018|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Morgan wrote a letter to Trump formally applying to become [[White House Chief of Staff]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2018/12/11/piers-morgan-trump-chief-of-staff/|title=Celebrity Apprentice Winner Piers Morgan Asks to Be Trump's Chief of Staff|website=Fortune|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring Trump's [[state visit]] to the United Kingdom in [[List_of_presidential_trips_made_by_Donald_Trump_(2019)#June|June 2019]], Morgan once again interviewed Trump, this time at the [[Churchill War Rooms]].<ref>{{cite news |title=ITV to broadcast Piers Morgan's Donald Trump interview in prime-time slot |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2019-06-05/piers-morgan-donald-trump-gmb-interview-how-to-watch-itv-repeat/ |accessdate=9 June 2019 |work=Radio Times |date=5 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Ofcom complaints ==\n===Chinese mocking and racism accusations===\n\nDuring his career at ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'', Morgan has been the subject of thousands of complaints to the British watchdog, [[Ofcom]] relating to controversial comments. On 21 January 2020, Morgan was accused of racism and was hit by 1,095 Ofcom complaints<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heart.co.uk/showbiz/celebrities/piers-morgan-ofcom-complaints-chinese-mock/|title=Piers Morgan hit with 1095 Ofcom complaints after 'mocking Chinese language' on GMB|website=Heart|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/europe/article/3047137/racism-row-erupts-after-queen-elizabeths-oldest-grandson-peter|title=Royally milking it: race row after queen\u2019s grandson stars in Chinese ad|date=22 January 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> for his comments relating to a Chinese dairy advert, in which he said \"He's using ching chong ching milk\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/21/piers-morgan-horrifies-viewers-mocks-chinese-language-rant-peter-phillips-milk-ad-12092997/|title=Piers Morgan horrifies viewers as he mocks Chinese language on GMB|date=21 January 2020|website=Metro|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> Morgan also spoke over the advert, saying \"ching chang cho jo\". He was accused by online netizens as using language which is used to antagonise Chinese people and for mocking the Chinese language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/news/morgan-labelled-racist-over-impression/3926807/|title=Piers Morgan labelled \u2018racist\u2019 over impression|website=Morning Bulletin|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Penguin and gender neutrality comments===\n\nOn 11 September 2019, Morgan claimed he identified himself as \"a penguin\" in response to a news piece relating to gender neutrality, and said \"the world has gone nuts\" over gender. This attracted 950 [[Ofcom]] complaints from viewers. He was cleared of any wrongdoing in November 2019, and in response, Morgan admitted \"he was personally quite pleased\" with having one of the highest number of complaints to any British TV show in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/11/05/piers-morgan-feels-empowered-receiving-record-breaking-complaints-identifying-penguin-11042269/|title=Piers Morgan \u2018empowered\u2019 after complaints for identifying as a penguin|date=5 November 2019|website=Metro|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/piers-morgan-cleared-ofcom-over-20813491|title=Piers Morgan cleared by Ofcom over 950 complaints \u2013 but Susanna Reid in trouble|last=O'Sullivan|first=Kyle|date=5 November 2019|website=mirror|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\n\nOn 22 January 2018, during a story about a homeless [[Special Air Service|SAS]] veteran, who had a petition set up in his name calling on his local council to provide him with social housing, Morgan had refused to read out [[Herefordshire Council]]'s statement. This was judged by Ofcom to be unfair to the council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ofcom.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/121347/Issue-362-of-Ofcoms-Broadcast-and-On-Demand-Bulletin.pdf|title=OfCom|date=24 September 2018|website=Ofcom \u2013 complaint by Herefordshire County Council, Good Morning Britain|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2016, Ofcom received 70 complaints in relation to comments made by Morgan during interview with Christian magistrate Richard Page about gay marriage, that viewers felt \"implied Christians were homophobic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/style/celebrity/celebrity-news/ofcom-clears-piers-morgan-over-christianity-questions-on-good-morning-britain-34617691.html|title=Ofcom clears Piers Morgan over Christianity questions on Good Morning Britain|website=independent|access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> Ofcom confirmed on 13 April 2016, that Morgan would not be investigated for his comments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/apr/11/piers-morgan-escapes-censure-over-christian-homophobe-remark|title=Piers Morgan escapes censure over Christian homophobe remark|date=11 April 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 February 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2015, Morgan was criticised by Ofcom for laughing as a guest repeatedly used the F-word live on air. Although Ofcom did not take action as his co-presenter [[Susanna Reid]] quickly apologised, the watchdog expressed concern at his behaviour.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/jun/15/piers-morgan-good-morning-britain-swearing|title=Piers Morgan criticised for laughing as Good Morning Britain guest swore on air|date=15 June 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 February 2020|last2=agencies|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Feuds==\n===Ian Hislop===\nMorgan appeared as a guest on the [[BBC]] satirical news quiz ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'' in an episode transmitted on 24 May 1996.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/have-i-got-news-for-you/felix-dexter-piers-morgan-clive-anderson/episode/143355/summary.html Have I Got News for You Episode Guide > Season 11, Episode 6] TV.com</ref> In it, show regular [[Ian Hislop]] accused Morgan of having him [[Stalking|followed]] and having his house watched. The conflict escalated and at one point the host, [[Angus Deayton]], asked if they wished to go outside and have a fight. Later on, guest panellist [[Clive Anderson]] confronted Morgan commenting, \"the last time I was rude to you, you sent photographers to my doorstep the next day\", to which Piers Morgan retorted, \"You won't see them this time.\" The audience responded loudly in favour of Hislop.<ref>''[[Have I Got News For You]]'' BBC2, Series 11 episode 6; Transmitted on 24 May 1996</ref> \"We're about to start exposing the moon-faced midget\", Morgan was quoted as saying in 2002, to which Hislop responded, \"all he's been offering for information about my private life is a \u00a350 reward. My friends think that's not nearly enough.\"<ref name=\"Summerskill\" />\n\nIn 2007, Hislop chose Morgan as one of his pet hates on ''[[Room 101 (British TV series)|Room 101]]''.<ref name=R101>''[[Room 101 (British TV series)|Room 101]]'' BBC2, Series 11 episode 6; Transmitted on 9 February 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/room_101/episodes/11/6/ Room 101 Episode 11.6 \u2013 Ian Hislop] British Comedy Guide</ref> In doing so, Hislop spoke of the history of animosity between himself and Morgan and said that after their exchange on ''Have I Got News For You'' (which was shown as a clip), Morgan's reporters were tasked with trying to get gossip on Hislop's private life (including phoning acquaintances of Hislop), and photographers were sent in case Hislop did anything untoward or embarrassing while in their presence. Neither the reporters nor the photographers succeeded. Hislop also said that Morgan had attempted to quell the feud in an article in ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'', saying, \"The war is over. I'm officially calling an end to hostilities, at least from my end. I'm sure it won't stop him carrying on his 'Piers Moron' stuff\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=Emily |date=4 April 2011 |title=Piers Morgan: The Biography |url=http://www.johnblakepublishing.co.uk/e-store/Piers-Morgan-The-Biography.html |location=London |publisher=[[John Blake (journalist)#John Blake Publishing|John Blake Publishing Ltd]] |page= |isbn=978-1843583516 |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> (''[[Private Eye]]'', the fortnightly satirical magazine which Hislop edits, regularly calls Morgan 'Piers Moron')<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=What a moron |newspaper=[[Private Eye]] |date=20 December 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hattenstone |first=Simon |date=12 October 2013 |title=Piers Morgan: 'I want to be at the centre of the big stuff' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/oct/12/piers-morgan-shooting-straight |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ellison |first=Sarah |author-link=Sarah Ellison |date=November 2012 |title=Blood, Sweat, and Piers |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2012/11/piers-morgan-criticized-hated-than-ignored |newspaper=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Hislop, who was working on a [[World War I]] documentary at the time, responded by asking \"Is that an armistice or an unconditional surrender?\" Although [[Paul Merton]] \u2013 host of ''Room 101'' at the time and good friend of Hislop \u2013 agreed to put Morgan into ''Room 101'', he then comically rejected Morgan as being \"too toxic\" for ''Room 101''.<ref name=R101/><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/feb/10/broadcasting.tvandradio1 \"Room 101, BBC1\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 February 2007</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Anthony |first=Andrew |author-link=Andrew Anthony |date=20 April 2010 |title=Piers Morgan: The man with stars in his eyes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2010/jun/20/profile-piers-morgan |newspaper=The Observer |accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nIn October 2003, journalist and television personality [[Jeremy Clarkson]] reportedly emptied a glass of water over Morgan during the last flight of [[Concorde]] for some photographs published in the ''Mirror''.<ref name=\"Media Monkey\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2004/mar/17/mediamonkey.pressandpublishing|author=Media Monkey|title=Clarkson and Morgan in tabloid tussle|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 March 2004|accessdate=8 June 2008}}</ref> In March 2004, at the [[British Press Awards]], Clarkson punched Morgan three times during another argument.<ref name=\"Media Monkey\"/>\n\nOn 4 February 2014, transgender advocate [[Janet Mock]] appeared as a guest on ''Piers Morgan Live'' to discuss her memoir, ''Redefining Realness''. After the interview aired, Mock sent a series of tweets criticising Morgan for describing Mock as being \"formerly a man\". Morgan responded that he had \"never been treated in such a disgraceful manner\" by a guest. On 5 February, Mock appeared as a guest again to debate the dispute.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hedgecock |first=Sarah |url=http://gawker.com/piers-morgan-demands-apology-from-disgraceful-trans-w-1516913568 |title=Piers Morgan Demands Apology from \"Disgraceful\" Trans Woman Guest |accessdate=6 February 2014 |newspaper=Gawker |date=5 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140206203218/http://gawker.com/piers-morgan-demands-apology-from-disgraceful-trans-w-1516913568 |archivedate= 6 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nMorgan strongly objected to the [[2017 Women's March|Women's March on Washington]] on 21 January 2017, the day after [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Trump's inauguration]], describing protesters as \"rabid feminists\" and the multiple protests as being \"vacuous\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oppenheim|first1=Maya|title=Piers Morgan just accused Ewan McGregor of being 'paedophile-loving hypocrite'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/piers-morgan-ewan-mcgregor-accuse-paedophile-loving-hypocrite-good-morning-britain-no-show-t2-a7543911.html|accessdate=27 February 2017|work=The Independent|date=24 January 2017}}</ref> The actor [[Ewan McGregor]] disagreed with Morgan's statements on the women's march and pulled out of appearing on ''Good Morning Britain'' the following Tuesday after discovering Morgan would be interviewing him, along with Reid.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-38729770|title=Ewan McGregor and Piers Morgan row over Good Morning Britain appearance|work=BBC News|date=24 January 2017|accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref> Morgan accused McGregor of being a \"paedophile-loving hypocrite\" for his past support of [[Roman Polanski]].<ref name=\"Aitkenhead\">{{cite news|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/jan/28/piers-morgan-im-just-putting-opinions-out-there-its-my-job|title=Piers Morgan: 'I'm just putting opinions out there. It's my job'|work=The Guardian|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Banned guests===\nIn May 2011, Morgan banned actor [[Hugh Grant]] from his shows on CNN and ITV after Grant spoke out against the need for the tabloid press. On Twitter he responded: \"Hugh Grant is now banned, in perpetuity, from @PiersTonight and Life Stories and anything else I ever do. Tedious little man.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/piers-morgan-bans-tedious-little-man-hugh-grant-from-cnn-show/|title=Piers Morgan bans 'tedious little man' Hugh Grant from CNN show|work=Press Gazette|date=18 May 2011|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2012, MTV referred to the bad relations between Piers Morgan and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], reporting that \"Morgan has apparently felt slighted over the years by Madonna...he claims he was lied to by the singer's publicist\".<ref name=\"Kaufman\">\"Madonna Banned...\" by Gil Kaufman, MTV, 28 March 2012; [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1681945/madonna-banned-piers-morgan.jhtml retrieved 30 September 2012]</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, it was reported that Morgan had also banned actor [[Kelsey Grammer]]. Morgan himself claimed, \"Kelsey Grammer saw a photo of [[Camille Grammer|his ex-wife Camille]] in the open of our show and legged it.\"<ref>\"Kelsey Grammer Walks Out on Piers Morgan\", ABC News, 20 September 2012; [http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/09/kelsey-grammer-walks-out-on-piers-morgan retrieved 30 September 2012]</ref> ''[[TVGuide]]'' reported, \"All plans were still a go for the segment until Grammer actually got in the hot seat and saw the footage the producers had planned to peg to the segment, including a picture of his ex-wife\".<ref>\"Kelsey Grammer storms off set\" by Emily Gagne, ''TVGuide.ca'', 20 September 2012; [http://tvguide.ca/TVNews/Articles/120920_grammer_leaves_piers_EG.htm retrieved 30 September 2012].</ref> On 26 September 2012, Fox 11 Los Angeles reported that \"many say [it] was an ambush by Piers\".<ref>Official Facebook page: ''FOX 11 Flash'', 26 September 2012; [https://www.facebook.com/FOX11Flash retrieved 30 September 2012]</ref> ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' reported that \"before the interview was scheduled, it was made clear that Grammer would answer all questions, including those about [his ex-wife]. His sole request was not to show any images of her.\"<ref>\"Kelsey Grammer, Piers Morgan: Actor Barred...\", ''HuffPost'', 27 September 2012; [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/27/kelsey-grammer-piers-morgan-cnn_n_1919662.html retrieved 30 September 2012]</ref>\n\n==Phone hacking allegations==\nDuring Morgan's tenure as editor, the ''Daily Mirror'' was advised by Steven Nott that voicemail interception was possible by means of a standard PIN code. Despite staff initially expressing enthusiasm for the story it did not appear in the paper, although it did subsequently feature in a ''[[South Wales Argus]]'' article and on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] in October 1999. On 18 July 2011 Nott was visited by officers of [[Operation Weeting]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/press/this-scandal-is-all-my-fault-says-salesman-2332669.html|first=Matt|last=Blake|title=This scandal is all my fault, says salesman|newspaper=The Independent|date=6 August 2011|accessdate=6 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe came under criticism for his \"boasting\" about phone hacking from [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Louise Mensch]], who has since apologised for these accusations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-14346050 |work=BBC News |title=MP Mensch apologises to Piers Morgan for hacking slur |date=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, in a sequence of articles, political blogger [[Paul Staines]] alleged that while editor of the ''Daily Mirror'' in 2002 Morgan published a story concerning the affair of [[Sven-Goran Eriksson]] and [[Ulrika Jonsson]] while knowing it to have been obtained by [[phone hacking]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Young |first=Toby |author-link=Toby Young |date=29 July 2011 |title=The net closes around Piers Morgan |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/tobyyoung/100098912/the-net-closes-around-piers-morgan/ |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2011, Morgan was a witness by satellite link from the United States at the [[Leveson Inquiry]].<ref name=\"BBCLeverson\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16259941 \"Piers Morgan tells Leveson: Daily Mirror did not hack phones\"], BBC News, 20 December 2011</ref> While he said he had no reason to believe that phone hacking had occurred at the ''Mirror'' while he was in charge there, he admitted to hearing a recording of an answerphone message left by [[Paul McCartney]] for [[Heather Mills]], but refused to \"discuss where that tape was played or who made [it] \u2013 it would compromise a source.\"<ref name=\"BBCLeverson\"/> Appearing as a witness at the same Inquiry on 9 February 2012, Mills was asked under oath if she had ever made a recording of Paul McCartney's phone call or had played it to Piers Morgan; she replied: \"Never\".<ref name=\"anon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/leveson-inquiry/9071901/Leveson-Inquiry-Heather-Mills-vows-she-did-not-play-Paul-McCartney-messages-to-Piers-Morgan.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|title=Leveson Inquiry: Heather Mills vows she did not play Paul McCartney messages to Piers Morgan|date=9 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Michael Holden\">{{cite web|author=Michael Holden|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/09/us-britain-hacking-morgan-idUSTRE8181CL20120209|agency=[[Reuters]]|title=Beatle's ex-wife says Piers Morgan heard hacked call|date=9 February 2012}}</ref> She said that she had never authorised Morgan, or anybody, to access or listen to her voicemails.<ref name=\"anon\"/> Mills told the inquiry that Morgan, \"a man that has written nothing but awful things about me for years\", would have relished telling the inquiry if she had played a personal voicemail message to him.<ref name=\"Michael Holden\"/>\n\nOn 23 May 2012, ''[[Newsnight]]'' presenter [[Jeremy Paxman]] was a witness at the Leveson Inquiry. He recalled a lunch with the ''Mirror'' editor in September 2002 at which Morgan outlined the means of hacking into a mobile phone.<ref>Dan Sabbagh and Lisa O'Carroll [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/may/23/leveson-piers-morgan-paxman \"Piers Morgan told me how to hack a phone, says Jeremy Paxman\"], ''The Guardian'', 23 May 2012.</ref>\n\nOn 28 November 2012, the [[Channel 4]] documentary ''Taking on the Tabloids'', fronted by actor and phone hacking victim [[Hugh Grant]], showed footage from a 2003 interview with Morgan by the singer and phone hacking victim [[Charlotte Church]], during which he explained to her how to avoid answerphone messages being listened to by journalists. He said: \"You can access ... voicemails by typing in a number. Now, are you really telling me that journalists aren\u2019t going to do that?\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Matilda Battersby|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/video-from-2003-shows-piers-morgan-talking-about-phone-hacking-8364468.html|title=Video from 2003 shows Piers Morgan talking about phone hacking|newspaper=The Independent|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tntmagazine.com/news/uk/video-new-clip-surfaces-showing-piers-morgan-talking-to-charlotte-church-about-phone-hacking|title=Video: New clip surfaces showing Piers Morgan talking to Charlotte Church about phone hacking|newspaper=[[TNT (magazine)|TNT]]|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 November 2012, the official findings of the [[Leveson Inquiry]] were released, in which [[Lord Justice Leveson]] said that Morgan's testimony under oath on phone hacking was \"utterly unpersuasive\". He stated:  \"[The] evidence does not establish that [Morgan] authorised the hacking of voicemails or that journalists employed by TMG [Trinity Mirror Group] were indulging in this practice ... What it does, however, clearly prove is that he was aware that it was taking place in the press as a whole and that he was sufficiently unembarrassed by what was criminal behaviour that he was prepared to joke about it.\"<ref name=\"Mark Sweney\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2012-11-28/key-moments-from-the-leveson-inquiry |title=Key moments from the Leveson Inquiry |publisher=ITV News |date=28 November 2012 |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 December 2013, Morgan was interviewed, under caution, by police officers from Operation Weeting investigating phone hacking allegations at ''[[Mirror Group Newspapers]]'' during his tenure as editor.<ref>Martin Evans [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/phone-hacking/10638562/Piers-Morgan-questioned-by-police-over-phone-hacking.html \"Piers Morgan questioned by police over phone-hacking\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'',.co.uk, 14 February 2014</ref>\n\nOn 24 September 2014, the [[Trinity Mirror]] publishing group admitted for the first time that some of its journalists had been involved in phone hacking and agreed to pay compensation to four people who sued for the alleged hacking of voicemails.<ref>Gallivan, Rory and Zekaria, Simon (September 2014) [https://online.wsj.com/articles/trinity-mirror-admits-liability-over-phone-hacking-1411547673 \u201cTrinity Mirror Admits Liability Over Phone Hacking\u201d], ''The Wall Street Journal'', 24 September 2014. Retrieved 29 September 2014</ref><ref>Sweney, Mark (September 2014). [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/sep/28/trinity-mirror-phone-hacking-claims-compensation \u201cTrinity Mirror faces up to the financial fallout as phone-hacking claims mount\u201d], ''The Guardian'', 28 September 2014. Retrieved 29 September 2014.</ref> Six other phone-hacking claims had already been settled. The BBC reported that it had seen legal papers showing that although the alleged hacking could have taken place as early as 1998, the bulk of the alleged wrongdoing took place in the early 2000s when Morgan was the ''Daily Mirror'' editor.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">BBC News online [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-29339756 \u201cPhone-hacking: Trinity Mirror admits liability\u201d], BBC News online, 24 September 2014 (Retrieved 29 September 2014)</ref> The admissions by Trinity Mirror came whilst the London Metropolitan Police investigation into the phone hacking allegations was ongoing. Morgan has always denied any involvement in the practice.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nMorgan married Marion Shalloe, a hospital ward sister,<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> in 1991. The couple had three sons, Albert, Spencer, and Stanley, and divorced in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burrell|first=Ian|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/piers-morgan-hack-of-the-day-1898171.html|title=Piers Morgan: Hack of the day|work=The Independent|date=13 February 2010|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2019032771334/piers-morgan-rare-photo-three-sons-loose-women/|title=Rare photo of Piers Morgan and his 3 handsome sons revealed on Loose Women|date=27 March 2019|website=HELLO!|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> In June 2010, he married his second wife, journalist [[Celia Walden]], daughter of the former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[George Walden]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/7853270/Piers-Morgan-marries-the-Telegraphs-Celia-Walden.html|title=Piers Morgan marries Celia Walden|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Morgan announced in mid 2011 that the couple were expecting a child,<ref>http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20500210,00.html</ref> and on 25 November 2011, Walden gave birth to a daughter, Elise, her first child and Morgan's fourth.<ref>http://www.celebritybabyscoop.com/2012/11/27/first-glimpse-of-piers-morgans-daughter-elise</ref>\n\nMorgan is a fan of [[Premier League]] football club [[Arsenal F.C.]]<ref name=\"Morgan comments\">{{cite news|title='Wenger fails again' \u2013 Piers Morgan scathing of Arsenal boss after David Ospina howler|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/champions-league/wenger-fails-again-piers-morgan-scathing-of-arsenal-boss-after-david-ospina-howler-31569375.html|work=Irish Independent|date=14 October 2015}}</ref> He was an outspoken critic of former Arsenal manager [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]] and called for his sacking on many occasions. Speaking in defence of Wenger in 2015, former Arsenal goalkeeper [[Bob Wilson (footballer, born 1941)|Bob Wilson]] labelled Morgan an \"incredibly pompous individual\".<ref name=\"Arsenal\">{{cite news|last=Menezes|first=Jack de|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/piers-morgan-hurt-after-arsenal-legend-bob-wilson-questions-his-support-for-the-gunners-and-labels-10073107.html|title=Piers Morgan 'hurt' after Arsenal legend Bob Wilson questions his support for the Gunners and labels him a 'pompous individual'|work=The Independent|date=26 February 2015|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> When Arsenal midfielder [[Aaron Ramsey]] met Morgan on 26 April 2015, Ramsey refused to shake his hand due to the criticism he received from Morgan during the 2012\u201313 season. Morgan has responded by calling Ramsey 'whatshisname'.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/aaron-ramsey-well-within-his-rights-to-refuse-handshake-with-arsenal-fan-piers-morgan-says-ian-10209316.html \"Aaron Ramsey 'well within his rights' to refuse handshake with Arsenal fan Piers Morgan, says Ian Wright\"]. Independent. Retrieved 14 October 2015</ref>\n\nPolitically, Morgan identified as a supporter of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in a 1994 interview.<ref name=\"Davies1994\"/> In 2019 Morgan voted for the Kensington Conservative candidate in the 2019 UK General Election,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lbc.co.uk/politics/elections/general-election-2019/piers-morgan-reveals-how-he-voted-general-election/|title=Piers Morgan reveals how he voted in this year's General Election|website=LBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> after previously voting for the Animal Welfare Party. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/piers-morgan-declares-his-political-endorsement-ahead-of-the-general-election-10229934.html|title=Piers Morgan declares his political allegiance ahead of the vote and it's... unexpected|date=2015-05-07|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n<references />\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book| title=Secret Lives| year=1991| isbn=0-905846-95-8| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Blake|author2=John Sachs}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Private Lives of the Stars| year=1991| isbn=0-207-16941-1| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Angus and Robertson|author2=John Sachs}}\n* {{Cite book| title=To Dream a Dream: Amazing Life of Phillip Schofield| year=1992| isbn=1-85782-006-1| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Blake| url=https://archive.org/details/todreamdreamamaz00morg}}\n* {{Cite book| title=\"Take That\": Our Story| year=1993| isbn=1-85283-839-6| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Boxtree}}\n* {{Cite book| title=\"Take That\": On the Road| year=1994| isbn=1-85283-396-3| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Boxtree}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Va Va Voom!: A Year with Arsenal 2003\u201304| year=2004| isbn=0-413-77451-1| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Methuen}}\n* {{Cite book| title=The Insider: The Private Diaries of a Scandalous Decade| year=2005| isbn=0-09-190849-3 | last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Ebury Press| title-link=The Insider: The Private Diaries of a Scandalous Decade}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Don't You Know Who I am?| year=2007| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Ebury Press}}\n* {{Cite book| title=God Bless America: Misadventures of a Big Mouth Brit| year=2009| isbn=978-0-09-191393-9| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Ebury Press| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/godblessamericad0000morg}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Shooting Straight: Guns, Gays, God, and George Clooney| year=2013| isbn=978-1-4767-4505-3| last=Morgan| first=Piers| publisher=Gallery Books| url=https://archive.org/details/shootingstraight0000morg}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q557758|c=Category:Piers Morgan|n=Category:Piers Morgan|b=no|v=no|voy=no|wikt=no|s=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|q=no}}\n*